Ruby's motive for the killing remains unclear, but it is believed he may have been driven by a desire for publicity, sympathy, or both. Ruby was convicted of murder and sentenced to death, but died in prison in 1967 from lung cancer before his appeals could be exhausted. His death has been the subject of numerous conspiracy theories.

title: Cataño, Puerto Rico
text: Cataño is a municipality on the northern coast of Puerto Rico, bordering the San Juan Bay and the Atlantic Ocean. It is part of the San Juan Metropolitan Area. Cataño is known for its waterfront promenade, the Paseo del Morro, which offers scenic views of the San Juan Bay and El Morro Castle. The municipality is also home to the Luis Muñoz Marín International Airport, Puerto Rico's main airport. Cataño has a population of around 25,000 people and is a popular tourist destination for its beaches, restaurants, and nightlife.

title: Edward Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax
text: Edward Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax, KG, OM, GCB, GCMG, GCVO, PC (16 April 1881 – 23 December 1959) was a British statesman who served as Foreign Secretary from 1938 to 1940 and again from 1943 to 1945. He was a prominent figure in the Conservative Party and held several cabinet positions, including Secretary of State for India and Viceroy of India. Halifax was known for his efforts to appease Nazi Germany before the Second World War, and he was a leading advocate for the Munich Agreement.

title: EMusic
text: eMusic is a digital music store and streaming service that offers millions of songs in various genres. Founded in 1998, it was one of the first music download services. Unlike other platforms, eMusic focuses on independent artists and offers a catalog of curated music. eMusic offers a subscription-based service that allows unlimited streaming and downloads for a monthly fee. Subscribers can also purchase individual tracks and albums. eMusic's strength lies in its extensive collection of independent music, including genres like indie rock, folk, electronic, and jazz.

title: Donald M. Payne
text: Donald Milford Payne (December 17, 1934 – March 6, 2012) was an American politician who served as a U.S. Representative from New Jersey for 12 terms from 1989 until his death in 2012. A Democrat, he was the first African American to represent New Jersey in the U.S. Congress. Payne was a strong advocate for civil rights, education, and healthcare. He was also a vocal critic of apartheid in South Africa.

title: Jim Higgins (Irish politician)
text: Jim Higgins (born 20 May 1947) is an Irish Fine Gael politician. He has served as a Teachta Dála (TD) for the Carlow–Kilkenny constituency since 2011. Higgins was first elected to the Dáil in 2011 as a member for the Carlow–Kilkenny constituency. He was re-elected in 2016 and 2020. Higgins serves as the party's spokesperson on Education and Skills.

title: Arithmetic mean
text: The arithmetic mean, also known as the average, is the sum of a set of numbers divided by the number of numbers in the set. It is a measure of the central tendency of a set of data. The arithmetic mean is often used to summarize a set of data and to compare different sets of data. For example, the arithmetic mean of the set of numbers {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} is 3.

title: Aberration of light
text: Aberration of light is an apparent change in the direction of a light source due to the relative motion between the source and observer. This phenomenon is caused by the finite speed of light, which means that light takes time to travel from one point to another. As a result, when an observer is moving relative to a light source, the light will appear to come from a slightly different direction than it actually does. The amount of aberration depends on the relative speed between the source and observer.

title: Waterford Harbour
text: Waterford Harbour, also known as Loch Da Chaoch, is a natural harbour located in the south-east of Ireland, in the county of Waterford. It is the second-largest natural harbour in the country, spanning an area of approximately 50 square kilometres. The harbour is formed by the confluence of three rivers: the Suir, the Nore, and the Barrow. Waterford Harbour is a significant commercial port and fishing harbour, and it also supports a variety of recreational activities, such as sailing, kayaking, and fishing.

title: 1960s
text: The 1960s, also commonly referred to as the "Swinging Sixties," was a decade of significant social and cultural change. It was a time of political unrest and protest, as well as a period of artistic experimentation and innovation. The decade saw the rise of counterculture movements, such as the hippie movement, and the emergence of the civil rights movement. It was also a time of great technological advancement, with the first moon landing taking place in 1969.

title: Nescopeck, Pennsylvania
text: Nescopeck is a borough in Luzerne County, Pennsylvania, United States. As of the 2020 census, it had a total population of 1,483. Nescopeck was named after a Native American chief who lived in the area. The borough was incorporated in 1832. The first settlers in the area were predominantly Welsh and German. Nescopeck is home to the Nescopeck Creek, which is a tributary of the Susquehanna River. The borough is also home to Nescopeck State Park, which offers hiking, fishing, and camping opportunities. Nescopeck is a small town with a rich history and natural beauty.

title: Kensington, Minnesota
text: Kensington is a city in Douglas County, Minnesota, United States. The population was 292 at the 2010 census. Kensington is located on the banks of the Chippewa River. The city is home to the Kensington Runestone, a controversial artifact that some believe to be evidence of pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact. The stone is inscribed with runes that appear to describe a group of Scandinavian explorers who visited the area in 1362. The Kensington Runestone is on display in the Kensington Runestone Museum.

title: Uppsala General Catalogue
text: The Uppsala General Catalogue (UGC) is a catalogue of 129,211 galaxies and groups of galaxies that is based on data from the Uppsala Observatory's Third Catalogue of Galaxies. The catalogue was published in 1973 by astronomers Per Olof Lindblad and Bertil Lindblad. The UGC contains information on the positions, magnitudes, sizes, and morphological types of the galaxies. It is one of the most comprehensive and widely used catalogues of galaxies. The data in the UGC have been used to study a wide range of topics, including the large-scale structure of the universe.

title: Lehigh, Iowa
text: Lehigh is a city in Webster County, Iowa, United States. The population was 414 at the 2020 census, a decline from the 440 population in 2000. Lehigh is located in central Webster County, approximately 13 miles northwest of Fort Dodge. The city is situated at the intersection of Iowa Highway 175 and County Road D31. Lehigh is home to the Lehigh Valley Railroad, which is a short-line railroad that operates between Lehigh and Fort Dodge. The railroad is used to transport agricultural products and other freight.

title: Broad Street Line
text: The Broad Street Line is a subway line in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, operated by the Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority (SEPTA). It is the second busiest subway line in the SEPTA system, carrying over 100,000 passengers per weekday. The line runs from Fern Rock Transportation Center in Northwest Philadelphia to NRG Station in South Philadelphia, with 26 stations along its route. The Broad Street Line is known for its distinctive orange and cream-colored cars, which have been in service since the line's opening in 1928.

title: Ovarian cancer
text: Ovarian cancer is a type of cancer that starts in the ovaries, two small organs located on either side of the uterus in women. It is the most common type of gynecological cancer worldwide, affecting approximately one in every 70 women. The majority of cases occur in women over the age of 50, but it can also affect younger women. The symptoms of ovarian cancer can be vague and often go unnoticed until the cancer has spread, making it difficult to diagnose early. Common symptoms include bloating, pelvic or abdominal pain, difficulty eating or feeling full quickly, and frequent urination.

title: Siletz Reservation
text: The Siletz Reservation is a federally recognized Indian reservation in the U.S. state of Oregon. The reservation is home to the Confederated Tribes of Siletz Indians, which includes the descendants of several indigenous tribes that were forcibly relocated to the area in the mid-1850s. The Siletz Reservation covers an area of approximately 110,000 acres (45,000 ha) in Lincoln County, Oregon. The main population center on the reservation is the city of Siletz. The Siletz Reservation is governed by a tribal council, which is elected by the enrolled members of the Confederated Tribes of Siletz Indians.

title: Mark Lanegan
text: Mark Lanegan (November 25, 1964 – February 22, 2022) was an American singer, songwriter, and musician. He was known for his distinctive baritone voice and his dark and introspective lyrics. Lanegan was a member of several notable bands, including Screaming Trees, Queens of the Stone Age, and Gutter Twins. He also released a successful solo career, with albums such as "The Winding Sheet" (1990) and "Blues Funeral" (2012). Lanegan died at the age of 57 from Covid-19 related complications.

title: Sardine v
text: Sardine v is a slang term for the McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle, a twin-engine, all-weather tactical fighter aircraft developed in the United States. The nickname is derived from the fish sardine, which is known for its small size and abundance. As the F-15 is a relatively small and maneuverable fighter aircraft, it is often compared to a sardine in a can, which is packed tightly with other sardines.

title: Contradiction
text: Contradiction, in logic and rhetoric, is a statement that asserts the opposite of another statement. Contradictions are often used to create a paradox, or a statement that seems contradictory but may actually be true. For example, the statement "This statement is false" is a contradiction. If the statement is true, then it must be false, and if it is false, then it must be true. This paradox can be resolved by considering the statement in a different way. For example, the statement can be interpreted as saying "This statement is not true." In this case, the statement is true, because it is not true.

title: Non-measurable set
text: A non-measurable set is a set of real numbers that cannot be assigned a Lebesgue measure. The existence of non-measurable sets was first established by Giuseppe Vitali in 1905. Vitali's construction is based on the well-ordering of the real numbers, which allows him to define a set of real numbers that has no smallest element. The Vitali set is an example of a non-measurable set.

title: Penrose stairs

title: Quaternary
text: The Quaternary is the current and most recent geological period. It began 2.58 million years ago and continues to the present. The Quaternary is characterized by significant climatic fluctuations, particularly the cyclical occurrence of glacial and interglacial periods. These fluctuations have had a profound impact on the Earth's ecosystems and human evolution. The Quaternary is further divided into two epochs: the Pleistocene and the Holocene. The Pleistocene, which began around 2.58 million years ago, was marked by repeated periods of glaciation and deglaciation. The Holocene, which began around 11,700 years ago, has been a relatively stable period with a warm climate and relatively minor climatic fluctuations.

title: Symbel
text: Symbel, also known as the feast of winter solstice, was a communal feast held in ancient Germanic societies, particularly among the Anglo-Saxons and Norsemen. title: Sexual dimorphism
text: Sexual dimorphism, in biology, refers to the differences in physical or behavioral characteristics between males and females of the same species. These differences can range from subtle variations in size and shape to striking disparities in coloration, ornamentation, and behavior. Examples of sexual dimorphism can be seen throughout the animal kingdom. Male lions, for instance, have manes that give them a distinctive appearance from females. Peacock males exhibit elaborate tail feathers used in courtship displays. In humans, men tend to be taller and heavier than women, with broader shoulders and narrower hips.

title: Entity–relationship model
text: The entity-relationship model (ERM) is a data modeling technique that is used to create a graphical representation of the entities and relationships within a system. ERMs are often used to design databases, but they can also be used to create other types of models, such as business process models and object-oriented models. An ERM consists of two main components: entities and relationships. Entities represent the objects in the system, such as customers, products, and orders. Relationships represent the connections between entities, such as the relationship between a customer and an order. ERMs are a powerful tool for visualizing and understanding the structure of a system. They can be used to identify potential problems in a system, such as data redundancies and inconsistencies. ERMs can also be used to communicate the structure of a system to other stakeholders, such as developers and users.

title: Von Neumann universe

title: Parmelee, South Dakota
text: Parmelee is a town in Lyman County, South Dakota, United States. The population was 49 at the 2020 census. Parmelee was laid out in 1907, and named for Francis D. Parmelee, a railroad official. The town is located on the White River, and the economy is based on agriculture and tourism. Parmelee is home to the Lyman County Historical Society Museum, which houses exhibits on the history of the county and the town.

title: Sparta Township, Crawford County, Pennsylvania
text: Sparta Township is a township in Crawford County, Pennsylvania, United States. The population was 2,305 at the 2020 census. Sparta Township was founded in 1824 and is named after Sparta, Greece. The township is located in the northwestern corner of Crawford County and is bordered by Erie County to the north, Warren County to the east, and Mercer County to the south. The main industries in Sparta Township are agriculture and manufacturing. The township is home to several churches, schools, and businesses.

title: LaTanya Richardson
text: LaTanya Richardson Jackson (born October 21, 1949) is an American actress, director, and producer. She is best known for her roles in the films "Fried Green Tomatoes" (1991), "Malcolm X" (1992), and "The Fighting Temptations" (2003), and the television series "Ally McBeal" (1997-2002). She has also directed several films and television shows, including "Tuskegee Airmen" (1995) and "The Trip to Bountiful" (2014). In 2021, she received the Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Play for her role in "A Soldier's Play."

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
text: Speed 2: Cruise Control is a 1997 American action thriller film directed by Jan de Bont and starring Sandra Bullock, Jason Patric, Willem Dafoe, and Temuera Morrison. It is the sequel to the 1994 film Speed. The film follows Annie Porter (Bullock), a police officer who must stop a deranged computer hacker (Dafoe) from crashing a cruise ship into an oil tanker.

title: Chessboard
text: A chessboard is an 8×8 checkered gameboard used in the game of chess. Each square is called a cell, and the 64 cells are arranged in eight rows (called ranks) and eight columns (called files). The colors of the squares alternate between light and dark, forming an 8×8 grid. The chessboard is placed with a light square on the bottom-left corner. Each player starts the game with 16 pieces: one king, one queen, two rooks, two knights, two bishops, and eight pawns. The objective of the game is to checkmate the opponent's king, which occurs when the king is under immediate threat of capture (check) and cannot escape.

title: Thomas Coram Foundation for Children
text: The Thomas Coram Foundation for Children is a British charity established in 1739 by social reformer Thomas Coram. Its mission is to provide care and education for orphaned and abandoned children. Founded as the Foundling Hospital, it was the first institution in England to take in any abandoned child, regardless of background. Today, the Foundation continues to provide services to vulnerable children through residential care, fostering, adoption, and education programs. It is one of the largest and oldest charities in the UK, having helped over 100,000 children since its inception.

title: PGM-17 Thor
text: The PGM-17 Thor was an intermediate-range ballistic missile (IRBM) developed by the United States Air Force in the 1950s. It was designed to carry a nuclear warhead and was deployed in the United Kingdom and Italy. The Thor was a liquid-fueled missile with a range of about 1,500 miles (2,400 kilometers). It was launched from a fixed pad and was primarily intended to target the Soviet Union. The Thor was phased out of service in the late 1960s.

title: California Air Resources Board
text: The California Air Resources Board (CARB) is a state agency in California, United States, responsible for regulating air pollution. It is responsible for implementing state and federal environmental laws and regulations aimed at reducing air pollution from motor vehicles, fuels, and consumer products. CARB has set some of the nation's most stringent environmental regulations, including the state's greenhouse gas reduction goals and zero-emission vehicle mandates. It also works with other states and international organizations to address air pollution issues.

title: Brentwood, Pennsylvania
text: Brentwood is a borough in Allegheny County, Pennsylvania, United States. It is located 6 miles (9.7 km) southeast of downtown Pittsburgh, on the Monongahela River. As of the 2020 census, the borough population was 9,410. Brentwood is home to several parks, including Brentwood Park, which offers a playground, picnic areas, and a walking trail. The borough is also home to the Brentwood Library, which is part of the Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh system. Brentwood is served by the Brentwood Borough School District.

title: Dulé Hill
text: Dulé Hill is an American actor, dancer, and singer. He is best known for his roles as Charlie Young on The West Wing (2000–2006), Gus Gorman on Psych (2006–2014), and Alex Williams on Suits (2011–2019). Hill has also appeared in numerous films, including The Departed (2006), Holes (2003), and She's All That (1999). He has also performed on Broadway, starring in productions such as Stick Fly and After Midnight.

title: Grille (car)
text: Grille, in automotive terms, refers to the perforated opening at the front of a vehicle that allows air to enter the engine compartment for cooling. It not only serves a functional purpose but also contributes to the aesthetic design of the car. The grille's shape, size, and pattern can vary significantly depending on the make, model, and year of the vehicle. Some grilles feature intricate designs incorporating brand logos or other decorative elements, while others opt for a more understated look. The grille is an important component of a car's cooling system, ensuring an adequate supply of air to the radiator and engine. It helps dissipate heat and maintain optimal operating temperatures.

title: Gandy dancer
text: Gandy dancer, a term used in the United States, refers to railroad laborers who maintain railroad tracks. The term originated in the 1800s when Irish immigrants were primarily employed for this work. They would sing traditional Irish folk songs while working, and the term "gandy dancer" is thought to derive from the song "The Gander in the Praties." Gandy dancers used specialized tools such as picks, shovels, and crowbars to tamp down the track bed, replace ties, and maintain the rails. Their work was physically demanding and often dangerous, requiring them to work in all weather conditions.

title: Boeing CH-47 Chinook
text: The Boeing CH-47 Chinook is a heavy-lift, tandem-rotor helicopter designed and manufactured by Boeing Vertol for the U.S. Army. It is one of the longest-serving helicopters in the U.S. military and has been exported to over 20 countries. The Chinook is known for its durability and versatility, and has been used in a wide range of operations, including combat, medical evacuation, and disaster relief.

title: Cease and desist
text: Cease and desist is a legal term used in a letter or notice to demand that a person or entity stop a particular action or refrain from engaging in a specific activity. It is typically used when the sender believes that the recipient is violating their legal rights or causing harm to them or their property. The letter typically outlines the specific actions that must be ceased and the consequences of failing to comply. The recipient is given a deadline by which they must take action, and if they fail to do so, the sender may pursue legal remedies, such as filing a lawsuit.

title: Sonia Gandhi
text: Sonia Gandhi, born December 9, 1946, is an Italian-born Indian politician who served as the President of the Indian National Congress from 1998 to 2017 and from 2019 to 2022. She was married to Rajiv Gandhi, the former Prime Minister of India. Gandhi has held various positions within the Congress party, including General Secretary and Treasurer. She was the first woman to lead the party and the first foreign-born Indian to hold the Prime Ministership. Gandhi's tenure was marked by social welfare initiatives, including the National Rural Employment Guarantee Act and the Right to Information Act.

title: Aliens versus Predator (1999 video game)
text: Aliens versus Predator is a first-person shooter video game developed by Rebellion Developments and published by Fox Interactive. It was released for Microsoft Windows in February 1999. The game features three distinct campaigns, each played from the perspective of a different species: the Aliens, the Predators, and the Colonial Marines. The game received generally positive reviews, with praise for its graphics, gameplay, and atmosphere.

title: Glitch (music)
text: Glitch music is a genre of electronic music characterized by the intentional use of digital glitches, errors, and other imperfections. It emerged in the late 1990s and early 2000s, influenced by experimental electronic music, musique concrète, and glitch art. Glitch musicians often use software or hardware that intentionally creates or manipulates glitches, such as bitcrushers, sample rate reducers, and feedback loops. The resulting compositions can range from chaotic and noisy to ethereal and textural. Glitch music has been used in various contexts, including electronic dance music, experimental film, and sound art.

title: Caroline Di Cocco
text: Caroline Di Cocco is an American film producer and former talent agent. She is best known for producing such films as "The Croods" (2013), "The Croods: A New Age" (2020), and "Puss in Boots: The Last Wish" (2022). Di Cocco began her career as a talent agent at the William Morris Agency. She later joined DreamWorks Animation as a creative executive, where she helped develop films such as "Madagascar" (2005) and "Kung Fu Panda" (2008). In 2010, she was promoted to head of development at DreamWorks Animation. In 2013, Di Cocco left DreamWorks Animation to form her own production company, Animal Logic Entertainment. Her first film as a producer was "The Croods," which grossed over $587 million worldwide. She has since produced several other successful films, including "The Croods: A New Age" and "Puss in Boots: The Last Wish."

title: List of female United States Cabinet Secretaries
text: As of 2023, there have been nine female United States Cabinet Secretaries: Frances Perkins (Labor): Appointed in 1933, she was the first woman to serve in the Cabinet. Oveta Culp Hobby (Health, Education, and Welfare): Served from 1953 to 1955. Shirley Temple Black (Ambassador to the United Nations): Served from 1969 to 1974. Patricia Roberts Harris (Housing and Urban Development): Served from 1977 to 1979 and later as Health and Human Services Secretary from 1980 to 1981. Carla Anderson Hills (Housing and Urban Development): Served from 1989 to 1993. Donna Shalala (Health and Human Services): Served from 1993 to 2001. Janet Reno (Attorney General): Served from 1993 to 2001. Madeleine Albright (Secretary of State): Served from 1997 to 2001. Hillary Clinton (Secretary of State): Served from 2009 to 2013.

title: Charles Webster Leadbeater
text: Charles Webster Leadbeater (1854-1934) was a British occultist, theosophist, clairvoyant, and prolific writer. He was a prominent member of the Theosophical Society and a close associate of its founders, Helena Blavatsky and Henry Steel Olcott. Leadbeater claimed to have the ability to see the astral plane and to communicate with spiritual beings. He wrote extensively about his experiences, including works on theosophy, clairvoyance, and the afterlife. Leadbeater's writings were controversial, and he was accused of sexual misconduct. He was expelled from the Theosophical Society in 1906 and founded his own organization, the Liberal Catholic Church.

title: Louisiana Creole cuisine
text: Louisiana Creole cuisine is a unique blend of French, Spanish, African, and Native American culinary traditions. It is characterized by its use of fresh, local ingredients, such as seafood, vegetables, and spices. Creole dishes are often hearty and flavorful, with a focus on bold flavors and rich sauces. Some of the most popular Creole dishes include gumbo, jambalaya, and etouffée. These dishes are typically served with rice or pasta and are often accompanied by side dishes such as cornbread or salad. Louisiana Creole cuisine is a vibrant and delicious reflection of the state's diverse cultural heritage.

title: Malabo
text: Malabo, formerly known as Santa Isabel, is the capital and largest city of Equatorial Guinea. Situated on the north coast of Bioko Island, it serves as the country's administrative, economic, and cultural center. Known for its colonial-era architecture, Malabo boasts landmarks such as the Santa Isabel Cathedral and the Presidential Palace. The city's economy is driven by petroleum production, fishing, and tourism. Its vibrant cultural scene includes museums, theaters, and a wide range of music and dance performances. Malabo is home to a diverse population, reflecting the rich cultural heritage of Equatorial Guinea and its colonial past.

title: Indonesian cuisine
text: Indonesian cuisine is a diverse and flavorful blend of culinary traditions that have evolved over centuries. It is influenced by indigenous Indonesian cooking techniques, as well as foreign influences from India, China, and the Middle East. Indonesian cuisine is known for its use of aromatic spices and fresh ingredients, and dishes often feature a balance of sweet, salty, and spicy flavors. Popular dishes include nasi goreng (fried rice), gado-gado (vegetable salad with peanut sauce), and rendang (beef stew). Indonesian cuisine is a reflection of the country's rich cultural heritage and is enjoyed by people around the world.

title: Claddagh ring
text: The Claddagh ring is a traditional Irish ring that symbolizes love, loyalty, and friendship. The ring features two hands holding a heart, which is surmounted by a crown. The heart represents love, the hands represent friendship, and the crown represents loyalty. The Claddagh ring is often given as a gift to symbolize a romantic relationship or a close friendship. It can also be worn as a wedding ring or an engagement ring. The Claddagh ring has been worn in Ireland for centuries, and it remains a popular symbol of Irish culture today.

title: Patrick Feehan
text: Patrick Feehan (1829–1902) was an Irish-born American prelate of the Catholic Church. He served as the fourth Archbishop of Chicago from 1880 to 1902. Born in Tipperary, Ireland, Feehan emigrated to the United States in 1849. He studied for the priesthood in Missouri and was ordained in 1852. He served as a parish priest in St. Louis before becoming vicar general of the Archdiocese of St. Louis in 1878. As Archbishop of Chicago, Feehan oversaw a period of rapid growth for the archdiocese. He founded numerous parishes, schools, and hospitals. He also played a key role in the establishment of the Catholic University of America in Washington, D.C. Feehan is remembered as a gifted administrator and a tireless advocate for the poor and the working class.

title: 6th Dalai Lama
text: The 6th Dalai Lama, Tsangyang Gyatso (1683–1706), was a spiritual leader of Tibet and a renowned poet. Born in Mon, Tawang, he ascended to the throne at the age of two after the death of the 5th Dalai Lama. He was known for his unconventional behavior and controversial love affairs, which led to his abdication in 1706. Despite his short reign, he remains a revered figure in Tibetan Buddhism and is celebrated for his poetic works, which explored themes of love, spirituality, and exile.

title: Child labour
text: Child labor is the employment of children under the age of 18 in any work that deprives them of their childhood, interferes with their ability to attend regular school, and that is mentally, physically, socially or morally dangerous and harmful. Child labor is considered illegal and exploitative in many countries. However, in developing countries, it remains a common practice. There are an estimated 152 million child laborers worldwide.

title: First Transcontinental Railroad
text: The First Transcontinental Railroad was a groundbreaking achievement in American transportation history. Completed in 1869, it connected the eastern and western United States by rail for the first time, spanning over 1,900 miles. The railroad played a pivotal role in the development of the American West and the nation's economic growth. It enabled the transportation of goods and people across the vast continent, fostering trade and settlement. The railroad also spurred the growth of industries such as mining, agriculture, and tourism. Its completion marked a significant milestone in the nation's infrastructure and transportation system.

title: Warsaw Uprising
text: The Warsaw Uprising, codenamed Operation Tempest, was a significant military operation of the Polish Underground State against Nazi Germany in German-occupied Poland during World War II. It began on August 1, 1944, as part of a larger nationwide Operation Tempest. The Home Army, the dominant force of the Polish Underground State, launched the uprising with the aim of liberating Warsaw ahead of the advancing Soviet Red Army. The uprising was brutally suppressed by the Germans, resulting in massive civilian casualties and the near-total destruction of the city.

title: United States Secretary of Agriculture
text: The United States Secretary of Agriculture is the head of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) and a member of the United States Cabinet. The Secretary is appointed by the President of the United States, with the advice and consent of the United States Senate, and serves at the pleasure of the President. The Secretary is responsible for overseeing the USDA, which is responsible for developing and executing federal policy on farming, agriculture, forestry, and food. The current Secretary of Agriculture is Tom Vilsack.

title: TURBOchannel
text: TURBOchannel was a proprietary 16-bit computer bus architecture based on the Motorola 68000 microprocessor. Developed by Motorola in the early 1980s, it was designed for use in high-performance workstations and personal computers. TURBOchannel supported both 8-bit and 16-bit data transfers, multiple master/slave configurations, and a maximum data transfer rate of 10 MB/s. It was used in a number of Motorola computers, including the Motorola 68020 and 68030 systems, and was also licensed to other companies such as Apple Computer and Sun Microsystems.

title: Orange Coast College
text: Orange Coast College (OCC) is a public community college in Costa Mesa, California. Founded in 1947, it offers associate degrees and certificates in various fields, including arts and humanities, business, science and engineering, and social and behavioral sciences. OCC serves over 24,000 students annually and boasts a diverse student population. The college is known for its strong academic programs, particularly in the areas of nursing, biotechnology, and culinary arts. OCC also offers a range of student support services, including academic advising, counseling, and tutoring.

title: Ulaanbaatar
text: Ulaanbaatar, meaning "Red Hero", is the capital and largest city of Mongolia. Located in northern Mongolia, it is situated in the Tuul River Valley, on the northern slopes of the Bogd Khan Uul mountain range. As of 2022, it had a population of approximately 1.5 million, constituting over 40% of Mongolia's total population. Ulaanbaatar is the cultural, economic, and political center of the country, housing numerous historical landmarks, museums, universities, and government buildings.

title: Carter Lake, Iowa
text: Carter Lake is a city in Pottawattamie County, Iowa, United States. It is part of the Omaha-Council Bluffs metropolitan area. As of the 2020 census, the population was 3,784. The city was named after Robert Carter, who owned a trading post in the area in the 1840s. Carter Lake is located on the Missouri River, and the city's economy is largely based on tourism and recreation. The city is home to several casinos, restaurants, and bars. Carter Lake is also a popular spot for fishing, boating, and swimming.

title: East Weare Battery
text: East Weare Battery is a 19th-century gun battery located in Devon, England. Built between 1860 and 1865, it was part of the vast system of fortifications constructed around Plymouth to protect the city from naval attack. The battery is situated on a headland at the eastern end of Wembury Bay, and it was armed with a variety of guns, including one 10-inch rifled muzzle-loading gun and six 9-inch rifled muzzle-loading guns. The battery was manned by the Royal Artillery, and it played a role in coastal defense until the late 19th century. Today, East Weare Battery is open to the public and offers stunning views of the surrounding countryside.

title: Aerobot
text: Aerobot is a term used to describe a robot that is capable of flying. Aerobots are typically equipped with wings or propellers, and they can be either autonomous or remotely controlled. They are used for a variety of purposes, including surveillance, reconnaissance, and delivery. Aerobots have a number of advantages over traditional ground-based robots. They can access areas that are difficult or impossible to reach on the ground, and they can provide a bird's-eye view of the surroundings. This makes them ideal for tasks such as search and rescue operations, and for monitoring large areas of land.

title: The Special Goodness
text: The Special Goodness is a British brand of convenience food products manufactured by Princes Group. The brand was launched in 1993 and is known for its range of canned and frozen meals, including pasta dishes, curries, and pies. Target Marketing produces The Special Goodness brand under license from Princes Group. The brand experienced major rebranding in 2018, with a focus on affordability and value for money.

title: WKEF
text: WKEF is a television station in Dayton, Ohio, United States, affiliated with ABC. Owned by Sinclair Broadcast Group, it is the flagship station of the company's Dayton-Springfield-Cincinnati duopoly with Sinclair-owned CW affiliate WBDT in Dayton. The two stations share studios on South Dixie Drive in Dayton's Miami Township, and WKEF's transmitter is located off Wenger Road in Harrison Township, Ohio.

title: Off side
text: Offside is a rule in team sports such as football, ice hockey, field hockey, and basketball. It is designed to prevent players from gaining an unfair advantage by positioning themselves too close to the opposing team's goal or basket before the ball is in play. In offside positions, players are unable to receive the ball or puck directly from a teammate or take part in the active play. The exact definition of offside varies depending on the sport and its specific rules.

title: Movement for the Survival of the Ogoni People
text: The Movement for the Survival of the Ogoni People (MOSOP) is a Nigerian non-violent, social and environmental rights group. MOSOP was founded in 1990 by Ken Saro-Wiwa to advocate for the rights of the Ogoni people, an ethnic minority group in the Niger Delta region of Nigeria. MOSOP campaigns against environmental pollution caused by oil extraction in Ogoniland and for greater political autonomy and economic development. The group has also been involved in human rights activism, advocating for the release of political prisoners and an end to military dictatorship in Nigeria. MOSOP's activities have been met with violent repression by the Nigerian government, including the execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa and other MOSOP activists in 1995.

title: Geno's Steaks
text: Geno's Steaks is a famous cheesesteak restaurant in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, United States. It was founded in 1966 by Geno Vento and is known for its large, juicy cheesesteaks and long lines of customers. The restaurant has been featured in numerous television shows and movies and has become a popular tourist destination. Geno's is located in the South Philadelphia neighborhood and is open 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.

title: Jon Peter Lewis
text: Jon Peter Lewis (born December 11, 1973) is an American singer, songwriter, and music producer. He is best known as the lead singer and primary songwriter of the pop rock band En Vogue. Lewis has also written songs for other artists, including Brandy, Destiny's Child, and Whitney Houston. In addition to his music career, Lewis has also appeared as an actor in several films and television shows. He is married to singer-songwriter Traci Hale.

title: Croquet
text: Croquet is a lawn game played with mallets and wooden balls. The object of the game is to hit your ball through a series of hoops and then hit a stake at the end of the course. Croquet is thought to have originated in Ireland in the 18th century, and it quickly became popular in England and other parts of the world. Today, croquet is enjoyed by people of all ages and abilities. It is a fun and challenging game that can be played both competitively and recreationally.

title: Jessica Savitch
text: Jessica Savitch (November 19, 1947 – October 23, 1983) was an American television reporter and anchorwoman. She was the first female solo anchor of a network nightly news program when she joined NBC Nightly News in 1983. Savitch's career was marked by both success and controversy. She was known for her hard-hitting reporting style and her willingness to challenge authority. However, she also struggled with substance abuse and depression. In October 1983, she was killed in a car accident at the age of 35.

title: Brazzaville
text: Brazzaville, the vibrant capital city of the Republic of Congo, lies on the banks of the mighty Congo River, facing its twin city, Kinshasa, in the Democratic Republic of Congo. Founded in 1880 as a French colonial outpost, Brazzaville has grown into a bustling metropolis with a population of over 2 million people. It is the country's political, economic, and cultural hub, boasting a rich history, diverse culture, and a plethora of attractions, including the Pierre Savorgnan de Brazza Mausoleum, the Poto-Poto Market, and the Bacongo District.

title: A. J. Muste
text: Abraham Johannes Muste (January 8, 1885 – February 11, 1967) was a Dutch-born American pacifist, socialist, and Christian minister. He was a leading figure in the peace movement in the United States during the early 20th century, and he also played a significant role in the labor movement and the civil rights movement. Muste was a charismatic and influential speaker, and he was known for his commitment to nonviolence and social justice.

title: Oakmont, Pennsylvania
text: Oakmont is a borough in Allegheny County, Pennsylvania, United States. The population was 6,303 at the 2010 census. Oakmont is located along the Allegheny River, approximately 12 miles (19 km) northeast of downtown Pittsburgh. The borough is home to Oakmont Country Club, which has hosted the U.S. Open golf tournament nine times. Oakmont is also known for its historic downtown district, which features a variety of shops, restaurants, and businesses.

title: Li Bai
text: Li Bai (701-762), also known as Li Po, was a renowned Chinese poet of the Tang dynasty. Born in present-day Kyrgyzstan, Li Bai was a wanderer and adventurer who traveled extensively throughout China. His poems, known for their vivid imagery, lyrical beauty, and philosophical depth, have had a profound influence on Chinese literature. Li Bai is considered one of the greatest poets in Chinese history, and his work continues to be widely read and admired today.

title: Zheng Zhenduo
text: Zheng Zhenduo (1898–1981) was a Chinese writer, scholar, and bibliographer. He was a leading figure in the May Fourth Movement and is best known for his work on Chinese ancient literature and his efforts to promote Chinese folk culture. Zheng was the first dean of Peking University's Department of Chinese Language and Literature, and he later served as the president of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.

title: No Code
text: No Code refers to software development platforms that enable users to create applications without the need for traditional programming skills. These platforms provide a graphical user interface (GUI) and pre-built components that allow users to drag and drop elements, configure settings, and build functional applications. No Code empowers non-technical individuals and businesses to create custom software solutions without extensive coding experience. It has become increasingly popular due to its ease of use, speed, and ability to address specific business needs quickly and cost-effectively.

title: Gouverneur Morris
text: Gouverneur Morris (1752-1816) was an American statesman, diplomat, and Founding Father. He was a delegate to the Continental Congress and the Constitutional Convention, where he played a key role in drafting the Constitution. He later served as minister to France and as a senator from New York. Morris was a staunch advocate for a strong central government and for the expansion of American territory. He was also a prominent figure in the Federalist Party and a close associate of Alexander Hamilton.

title: Afghan Armed Forces
text: The Afghan Armed Forces are the military forces of Afghanistan, responsible for defending the country against external threats and maintaining internal security. They comprise the Afghan National Army, Afghan National Police, Afghan National Air Force, and Afghan National Special Forces. The Afghan Armed Forces were established in 2002 after the fall of the Taliban regime and have since been supported by the United States and other international allies.

title: Casablanca
text: Casablanca, a romantic war drama film, was released in 1942 and directed by Michael Curtiz. Set during World War II, it follows the story of Rick Blaine, an American expatriate who runs a nightclub in Casablanca, Morocco. When his former lover, Ilsa Lund, arrives with her husband, Victor Laszlo, a Czech resistance leader, Rick faces a moral dilemma between his love for Ilsa and his desire to help Victor escape from the Nazis. The film is renowned for its iconic lines, including "Play it, Sam" and "We'll always have Paris," and has become one of the most beloved and enduring films in cinema history.

title: History of Slovenia
text: Slovenia's history dates back to the Stone Age, with evidence of human habitation found in the country's numerous caves. In the 6th century AD, Slavic tribes settled in the area, and in the 8th century, they were conquered by the Frankish Empire. Slovenia remained under Frankish rule until the 10th century, when it became part of the Holy Roman Empire. In the 13th century, Slovenia was divided into several counties, which were ruled by local princes. In the 14th century, the Habsburg dynasty gained control of Slovenia, and the country remained under their rule for over 600 years. During the 19th century, Slovenia experienced a period of national awakening, and in 1848, the Slovene National Program was adopted. This program called for the unification of all Slovene lands and the recognition of the Slovene language and culture.

title: Field hockey
text: Field hockey is a team sport played on a field with a ball and sticks. Two teams of 11 players each compete to score goals by hitting the ball into the other team's net. The game is played on a rectangular field with goals at each end. Players use sticks to hit the ball around the field and to shoot it at the goal. Field hockey is a fast-paced and physical game that requires skill, speed, and endurance.

title: Alan McCombes
text: Alan McCombes (born 4 December 1964) is an English football agent and former professional footballer. As a player, he was a midfielder who made over 500 appearances in the Football League and Premier League for clubs including Manchester United, Manchester City, and Bolton Wanderers. McCombes represented England at youth international levels before making two appearances for the full national team in 1989. He retired from playing in 1997 and became a football agent.

title: Djurgårdens IF
text: Djurgårdens IF, also known as Djurgården, is a Swedish sports club based on the island of Djurgården in Stockholm. Founded in 1891, it is one of Sweden's oldest and most successful sports clubs, with over 30,000 members and 15 different sports sections. Djurgården's football team plays in the Swedish top flight, Allsvenskan, and has won the league title 12 times, most recently in 2019. The club also has a strong ice hockey team, Djurgårdens Hockey, which competes in the Swedish Hockey League.

title: Hi-hat
text: A hi-hat is a percussion instrument in the drum kit. It consists of two cymbals mounted on a stand, which are struck together by a foot pedal. Hi-hats are used to create a variety of rhythms and sounds, and are an essential part of many genres of music. The sound of a hi-hat can be varied by adjusting the tension of the cymbals, the distance between them, and the amount of pressure applied to the pedal. Hi-hats are typically played with the foot, but can also be played with sticks or mallets.

title: Cowards Bend the Knee
text: Cowards Bend the Knee is a 1903 American silent short Western film directed by Edwin S. Porter. The film depicts Billy, an outlaw, and his gang's attempt to rob a train, which is thwarted by a quick-thinking cowboy. The cowboy confronts Billy, who attempts to escape on horseback. The cowboy gives chase, and a gunfight ensues. Billy is ultimately killed by the cowboy. The film's title is a metaphor for the idea that cowards will always submit to those who are stronger or more determined.

title: Uzbekistan
text: Uzbekistan, officially the Republic of Uzbekistan, is a doubly landlocked country in Central Asia. It is bordered by Kazakhstan to the north, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan to the east, Afghanistan to the south, and Turkmenistan to the west. The capital and largest city is Tashkent. Uzbekistan covers an area of 447,400 square kilometers (172,700 sq mi) and has a population of over 34 million. The official language is Uzbek, and the currency is the Uzbek sum. Uzbekistan is a member of the United Nations, the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), and the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation (SCO). It is also an observer state in the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS).

title: Ross-on-Wye
text: Ross-on-Wye is a market town and civil parish in western Herefordshire, England. Located on the River Wye, it is 12 miles southwest of Hereford and 15 miles east of Abergavenny. The town has a population of around 10,000. Ross-on-Wye is known for its beautiful scenery, including the Wye Valley and the Forest of Dean. The town is also home to a number of historical landmarks, including Ross Castle and Wilton Castle. The town's economy is based on tourism, agriculture, and light industry. Ross-on-Wye is a popular destination for walkers, cyclists, and canoeists. The town also has a number of shops, restaurants, and pubs.

title: Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem
text: The Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem, also known as the Heine–Cantor theorem, is a fundamental theorem of mathematical analysis which states that every bounded sequence of real numbers has a convergent subsequence. This result is often used to prove the existence of solutions to certain types of equations and to establish the continuity of functions. The theorem is named after Bernhard Bolzano, Karl Weierstrass, Eduard Heine, and Georg Cantor, who independently discovered it in the 19th century.

title: Salford
text: Salford is a city in Greater Manchester, England, directly west of Manchester. The city lies between the River Irwell and the Manchester Ship Canal. Salford is first recorded in the Domesday Book of 1086. Salford developed rapidly in the 19th century as part of the Industrial Revolution. By 1850, Salford was a major centre for cotton manufacturing, engineering, and shipbuilding. The city was also home to a large number of Irish immigrants. Salford's population peaked in 1911 at 231,357, but has since declined. Today, Salford is a diverse and vibrant city with a population of around 255,000 people.

title: Brzeg
text: Brzeg is a town in southwestern Poland, situated on the Oder River. It is part of the Opole Voivodeship, and the seat of Brzeg County. As of 2019, the town has a population of around 35,000. Brzeg was first mentioned in 1250 and received town rights in 1254. It was an important center of trade and commerce in the Middle Ages, and its strategic location on the Oder River made it a frequent target of invasions. Brzeg's most notable landmark is Brzeg Castle, which was built in the 13th century and expanded over the centuries. The castle is now a museum and a popular tourist destination.

title: Honour
text: Honour, also spelled honor, is a virtue that is highly valued in many cultures. It is typically characterized by a sense of integrity, honesty, and fairness. People who are honorable are often respected and admired by others. There are many different ways to show honour, such as keeping one's word, being truthful, and respecting the rights of others.

title: Dan Aykroyd
text: Dan Aykroyd is a Canadian actor, comedian, screenwriter, and producer. He is best known as a cast member of the NBC sketch comedy show Saturday Night Live from 1975 to 1979. Aykroyd has starred in numerous films, including The Blues Brothers (1980), Ghostbusters (1984), Driving Miss Daisy (1989), and Coneheads (1993). He has also written and produced several films, including The Coneheads Movie (1993) and Blues Brothers 2000 (1998). Aykroyd has won two Emmy Awards and a Golden Globe Award.

title: Green Party (Ireland)
text: The Green Party is a political party in Ireland. It was founded in 1981 and is a member of the European Green Party. The party's policies are based on environmentalism, social justice, and grassroots democracy. The Green Party has had representation in the Dáil Éireann since 1989 and currently has 12 TDs, including the party leader Eamon Ryan. The party also has representation in the Seanad Éireann and in local government.

title: Van Diemen's Land
text: Van Diemen's Land was the historical name for the island of Tasmania, Australia. It was named after Anthony van Diemen, the Governor-General of the Dutch East Indies, who visited the island in 1642. The name was officially changed to Tasmania in 1856. Van Diemen's Land was first settled by the British in 1803 as a penal colony. It became a popular destination for convicts, and over 100,000 were transported to the island during the 19th century. The colony was also used as a place of exile for political prisoners, including Irish rebels and Indian sepoys.

title: Atmospheric sciences
text: Atmospheric sciences, a branch of Earth science, investigates Earth's atmosphere and its processes. It encompasses atmospheric chemistry, cloud physics, meteorology, and climatology. Atmospheric scientists study gases, aerosols, clouds, rain, snow, air pollution, and atmospheric circulation patterns. They use weather balloons, satellites, and computer models to observe, analyze, and predict atmospheric phenomena, contributing to weather forecasting, climate change studies, and air quality management.

title: Clatsop County, Oregon
text: Clatsop County is the northwesternmost county in the U.S. state of Oregon. As of the 2020 census, the population was 40,363. The county seat is Astoria. Clatsop County was created on June 22, 1844, from a portion of Polk County. The county is named after the Clatsop tribe, a Native American people who lived in the area. Clatsop County is home to Fort Clatsop, which was the winter camp of the Lewis and Clark Expedition from December 1805 to March 1806.

title: Hermosillo
text: Hermosillo, officially Hermosillo de la Constitución, is the capital and largest city of the Mexican state of Sonora. It is located in the northwest of the country, in the Sonoran Desert. As of 2020, the city had a population of 916,748, while the metropolitan area had a population of 1,068,225. Hermosillo is the economic, political, and cultural center of Sonora. It is home to several universities, museums, and theaters. The city is also known for its vibrant nightlife and cuisine.

title: Anaxagoras
text: Anaxagoras was a pre-Socratic Greek philosopher who lived in the 5th century BCE. He is best known for his theory that all matter is composed of an infinite number of qualitatively distinct and unchanging particles called "seeds". Anaxagoras also believed that Mind or Intelligence (Nous) was the cause of all things, and that it acted on the seeds to bring about order and structure in the universe. Although his theories were later superseded, Anaxagoras' ideas had a significant influence on subsequent philosophical thought, including the work of Plato and Aristotle.

title: Koshigaya
text: Koshigaya is a city located in Saitama Prefecture, Japan. It is situated in the southern part of the prefecture, approximately 20 kilometers northeast of Tokyo. As of 2023, the city has a population of around 325,000, making it the fifth most populous city in Saitama. Koshigaya is known for its large-scale residential developments and its proximity to Tokyo, making it a popular commuter town. The city is also home to several cultural attractions, including the Koshigaya Municipal Museum and the Koshigaya Lake Town Festa.

title: Judaism
text: Judaism is the monotheistic religion of the Jewish people, characterized by its belief in a single God and the importance of religious law and tradition. The central sacred texts of Judaism are the Torah, the Nevi'im (Prophets), and the Ketuvim (Writings), collectively known as the Tanakh or Hebrew Bible. The Torah, the first five books of the Tanakh, contains the foundational stories, laws, and commandments of Judaism.

title: Jenson Button
text: Jenson Alexander Lyons Button (born 19 January 1980) is a British former racing driver. He won the 2009 Formula One World Championship driving for Brawn GP. Button began his career in karting before moving to single-seaters in 1998. He made his Formula One debut in 2000 with Williams, and raced for the team until 2002. He then moved to BAR, where he remained until the team was bought out by Honda in 2006. Button stayed with Honda until the team withdrew from Formula One at the end of 2008. In 2009, he joined Brawn GP, which was formed from the ashes of Honda. Button won six races during the 2009 season, including the British Grand Prix, and secured the World Championship with one race to spare.

title: Fishers, Indiana
text: Fishers is a city in Hamilton County, Indiana, United States. As of the 2020 census, the population was 98,977, making it the 10th largest city in Indiana. The city is located approximately 20 miles (32 km) northeast of downtown Indianapolis. Fishers is part of the Indianapolis metropolitan area and is the largest city in Hamilton County. The city is home to the Nickel Plate District, a mixed-use development that includes restaurants, shops, and apartments. Fishers is also home to Connor Prairie, an interactive history park.

title: Cockchafer
text: The cockchafer is a large beetle of the family Scarabaeidae, found in Europe and North Africa. It is a nocturnal insect, and feeds on leaves of trees and shrubs. The larvae of the cockchafer are known as leatherjackets, and they live in the soil, feeding on roots. The cockchafer is a common pest of agricultural crops, and can cause significant damage to plants. It is also known to be a nuisance to humans, as it can fly into homes and swarm around lights.

title: Shell Centre
text: Shell Centre is a commercial office complex located on the South Bank of the River Thames in London, England. The complex was designed by the British architect, Sir Denys Lasdun, and completed in 1962. It is composed of three towers and a connecting block, and was constructed to house the headquarters of the Royal Dutch Shell Group. The Centre has since been expanded and refurbished, and now includes a variety of retail and leisure facilities. It is a Grade II* listed building, and is considered to be one of the most important examples of Brutalist architecture in the United Kingdom.

title: Paper embossing
text: Paper embossing is a decorative technique that creates a raised design on paper. It is achieved by pressing a die or roller with a raised design into the paper, applying pressure to create a three-dimensional effect. Embossing can be used to add texture, depth, and visual interest to paper, making it an effective technique for creating personalized stationery, invitations, greeting cards, and other paper crafts.

title: Colima
text: Colima is a state in Southwestern Mexico. It is bordered by the states of Jalisco to the north, Michoacán to the northeast, and Guerrero to the east. Colima also has a coastline on the Pacific Ocean to the west. The capital city is Colima. The state has an area of 5,625 square kilometers (2,172 square miles) and a population of over 731,000. The climate is tropical, with an average temperature of 25 degrees Celsius (77 degrees Fahrenheit). The main economic activities are agriculture, fishing, and tourism.

title: Bark (botany)
text: Bark is the outermost layer of the stems and roots of woody plants. It consists of dead and living cells and protects the internal tissues from damage, dehydration, and pathogens. Bark is composed of several layers, including the cork cambium, cork, phelloderm, and phloem. The cork cambium produces cork cells, which are filled with suberin, a waxy substance that makes the bark waterproof. The phelloderm is a living tissue that lies between the cork and the phloem. The phloem is a living tissue that transports nutrients from the leaves to the roots.

title: Doomsday argument
text: The Doomsday argument is a philosophical argument that predicts a low probability of any human being being born in a particular generation if humanity survives for a long time. This is because, if humanity survives for a long time, then there will be many more generations of humans in the future than there are now. So, any one person's chance of being born in a particular generation is very small.

title: Ľudovít Štúr
text: Ľudovít Štúr (1815-1856) was a Slovak nationalist leader, writer, and linguist. He is considered one of the most important figures in Slovak history and is credited with helping to establish a distinct Slovak national identity. Štúr was born in Zohor, then part of the Kingdom of Hungary. He studied at the Lutheran lyceum in Bratislava and later at the University of Halle in Germany. After returning to Slovakia, he became a leading figure in the Slovak national movement. In 1843, he co-founded the Slovak National Council, which sought to promote Slovak culture and language. He also wrote extensively on Slovak history and culture and is considered one of the founders of modern Slovak literature.

title: Kennedy Professor of Latin
text: The Kennedy Professor of Latin is a chair in Classics at the University of Cambridge, England. The professorship was founded by Benjamin Kennedy in 1869 and is one of the most prestigious positions in the field of Classics. The Kennedy Professor is responsible for teaching and research in Latin language and literature, and for overseeing the Faculty of Classics. Notable holders of the chair have included Arthur Woollgar Verrall, John Edwin Sandys, and Michael Lapidge.

title: Battle of Smolensk (1812)
text: The Battle of Smolensk (1812) was a major engagement of the Napoleonic Wars, fought between the French Empire and the Russian Empire. The battle took place from August 16 to 18, 1812, near the city of Smolensk, Russia. The French army, led by Napoleon Bonaparte, attacked the Russian army, led by Mikhail Barclay de Tolly. The battle was inconclusive, with both sides suffering heavy losses. However, the battle was a strategic victory for the Russians, as it delayed the French advance on Moscow and gave the Russians time to prepare for the upcoming Battle of Borodino.

title: Sverre of Norway
text: Sverre Sigurdsson (c. 1151 – March 9, 1202) was King of Norway from 1184 until his death in 1202. He was a member of the House of Sverre, a cadet branch of the Fairhair dynasty. Sverre was an illegitimate son of King Sigurd Munn. He grew up in the Faroe Islands and the Hebrides before returning to Norway in 1177. He quickly rose to prominence as a leader of the Birkebeiner faction, a group of rebels who opposed King Magnus V Erlingsson. Sverre defeated Magnus in 1184 and became king. He faced several challenges during his reign, including invasions from Denmark and Sweden, but he successfully defended his kingdom and expanded its borders.

title: Therese Brandl
text: Therese Brandl (1871-1921) was an Austrian physicist and the first woman to graduate from the University of Vienna with a doctorate in physics. She faced significant discrimination due to her gender, limiting her career opportunities. Despite these challenges, Brandl made important contributions to the understanding of radioactivity, including the discovery of the alpha decay constant. She became the first woman to lead a physics laboratory at the University of Vienna. Her work paved the way for future women in physics, inspiring others to overcome societal barriers.

title: Magdalenian
text: The Magdalenian is a Late Stone Age culture that emerged in southwestern Europe around 17,000 years ago. It is named after the La Madeleine rock shelter in France, where many artifacts from this period were first discovered. Magdalenian people were highly skilled hunters and artists. They produced a wide range of stone tools, including spear points, scrapers, and burins. They also made bone and antler tools, such as needles, awls, and harpoons. Magdalenian art is known for its realistic depictions of animals, particularly horses, bison, and reindeer. These images were often painted on cave walls or carved into bone or antler.

title: Farley Mowat
text: Farley Mowat (1921-2014) was a Canadian author and environmentalist. He is best known for his novels about the Canadian Arctic, including "Never Cry Wolf" (1963), "Owls in the Family" (1961), and "The Sea Hunters" (1967). Mowat's work often explores the relationship between humans and nature, and he was a passionate advocate for environmental protection. He received numerous awards for his writing, including the Governor General's Award for English-language fiction.

title: Omsk
text: Omsk is a city in southwestern Siberia, Russia, and the administrative center of Omsk Oblast. It is situated at the confluence of the Irtysh and Om Rivers, approximately 2,200 kilometers east of Moscow. Omsk is the second-largest city in Siberia and the eighth-most populous city in Russia, with a population of over 1.1 million. The city is a major industrial and transportation hub, with industries including oil refining, petrochemicals, and manufacturing. Omsk is also home to several universities and research institutions, making it a significant educational and scientific center.

title: Okemah, Oklahoma
text: Okemah, Oklahoma, is a city in Okfuskee County. It is the county seat and the largest city in the county. The population was 3,069 at the 2020 census, making it the 219th largest city in Oklahoma. The city is named after the Choctaw word for "homeland." Okemah is located in eastern Oklahoma, approximately 70 miles (110 km) east of Oklahoma City. The city is home to the Woody Guthrie Center, which is dedicated to preserving the legacy of the folk singer Woody Guthrie, who was born in Okemah.

title: Yma Sumac
text: Yma Sumac (September 13, 1922 – November 1, 2008) was a Peruvian soprano known for her extraordinary vocal range, spanning five octaves. She was born Zoila Augusta Emperatriz Chávarri del Castillo in Ichocán, Peru, and studied music in Lima. Sumac's career took off in the 1950s, with her unique vocal abilities and exotic stage persona captivating audiences worldwide. She released several albums and performed in films, becoming an international sensation. Sumac's music blended elements of traditional Peruvian folk music with Western classical and popular styles, creating a distinctive sound that continues to inspire musicians and listeners to this day.

title: Ethical Culture Fieldston School
text: Ethical Culture Fieldston School, originally two separate schools, merged in 1991 to form the present institution on three campuses in New York City and neighboring Riverdale: Fieldston Lower (pre-kindergarten through 5th grade), Fieldston Middle (6th through 8th grade), and Fieldston Upper (9th through 12th grade). Ethical Culture Fieldston School emphasizes academic excellence, ethical development, public service, and social justice, embracing the values of humanism and democratic ideals. It is known for its strong academics, diverse student body, and commitment to extracurricular activities.

title: Rational ClearCase
text: Rational ClearCase is a software configuration management (SCM) tool from IBM. It is used to manage and track changes to software code, documentation, and other artifacts throughout the development lifecycle. ClearCase uses a centralized repository to store all project artifacts, and it provides a variety of features to help teams collaborate on software projects, including version control, branching, merging, and conflict resolution. ClearCase is available in both on-premises and cloud-based versions.

title: Discography: The Complete Singles Collection
text: "Discography: The Complete Singles Collection" is a 4-disc compilation album by English singer-songwriter David Bowie, released in 2018. The album features every A-side and B-side single released by Bowie during his lifetime, spanning his career from 1964 to 2016. The collection includes over 100 tracks, showcasing Bowie's diverse range of musical styles and iconic hits such as "Space Oddity," "Changes," and "Heroes." The album also features rare and previously unreleased recordings, making it a comprehensive retrospective of Bowie's unparalleled artistry.

title: Jan Fabre
text: Jan Fabre (born 1958) is a Belgian conceptual and performance artist, sculptor, playwright, theatre director, and designer. Fabre's work often explores themes of metamorphosis, the human body, and the relationship between art and science. He is known for his provocative and experimental performances, which have included live animal dissections, the use of human blood, and the exploration of taboo subjects. Fabre's work has been exhibited in major museums and galleries around the world, and he has received numerous awards and accolades for his contributions to the arts.

title: Idaho Transfer
text: Idaho Transfer is a women's college basketball team that competes in the Big Sky Conference. The team is based in Pocatello, Idaho, and plays its home games at Reed Gym. Idaho Transfer is one of the most successful women's basketball programs in the Big Sky Conference, having won 10 regular season championships and 5 tournament championships. The team has also made 10 NCAA Tournament appearances, including four Sweet Sixteen appearances. The team is led by head coach Brian Orr, who is in his 10th season at the helm of the program.

title: Durness
text: Durness is a small village in Sutherland, Scotland. It is located on the north-west coast of the country, overlooking the Atlantic Ocean. The village is a popular tourist destination, with many visitors coming to see the nearby beaches, cliffs, and mountains. Durness is also home to a number of historical sites, including the ruins of Durness Castle. The village has a population of around 400 people.

title: Microsoft Office
text: Microsoft Office is a proprietary office suite of applications developed by Microsoft for Windows, macOS, iOS, and Android. It includes Microsoft Word, Excel, PowerPoint, OneNote, Outlook, Publisher, and Access. The suite is available in several editions, including Home & Student, Home & Business, Professional, and Enterprise. Microsoft Office is widely used by businesses and individuals for creating and editing text documents, spreadsheets, presentations, databases, and other types of files. It is also compatible with a variety of file formats, including DOCX, XLSX, PPTX, and PDF.

title: University of New Hampshire
text: The University of New Hampshire (UNH) is a public research university located in Durham, New Hampshire. Founded in 1866 as the New Hampshire College of Agriculture and the Mechanic Arts, UNH is New Hampshire's flagship public university, offering undergraduate, graduate, and professional programs. UNH's academic reputation is ranked among the top 200 national universities by U.S. News & World Report. The university is particularly renowned for its programs in marine science, environmental science, and engineering. UNH also has strong research programs in biomedical sciences, social sciences, and the arts.

title: Alessandro Santos
text: Alessandro Santos (born March 12, 1977) is a Brazilian-American professional basketball coach and former player. He is currently the assistant coach for the Philadelphia 76ers of the National Basketball Association (NBA). As a player, Santos was a 6'9" center who played professionally in Brazil, Spain, and the NBA. He was selected with the 32nd overall pick in the 1999 NBA draft by the Philadelphia 76ers, with whom he spent the majority of his NBA career.

title: William Price (physician)
text: William Price (1779–1839) was a Welsh physician known for his work in the field of mental illness. He is considered one of the pioneers of the humane treatment of the mentally ill. Price was born in Merthyr Tydfil, Wales, in 1779. He studied medicine at the University of Edinburgh and graduated in 1805. In 1811, he founded the first private asylum in Wales, the Whitland Asylum, which became a model for other asylums in the country. Price was a strong advocate for the humane treatment of the mentally ill. He believed that patients should be treated with respect and compassion, and he opposed the use of physical restraints and other harsh methods. He also believed that patients could be cured of their illnesses, and he developed a number of innovative treatments, including hydrotherapy, music therapy, and occupational therapy.

title: Zalmay Khalilzad
text: Zalmay Khalilzad (born March 22, 1951) is an Afghan-American diplomat and politician. He served as the United States Ambassador to Afghanistan from 2003 to 2005 and as the United States Ambassador to Iraq from 2005 to 2007. Khalilzad is currently a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution and a visiting professor at the University of California, Berkeley. He is also the founder and chairman of the Khalilzad Group, a strategic consulting firm specializing in international relations and public policy.

title: Arrested Development (TV series)
text: Arrested Development is an American sitcom created by Mitchell Hurwitz that originally aired on Fox from November 2, 2003, to February 10, 2006. The show follows the Bluth family, a wealthy family who lose their fortune and are forced to live together in a small apartment. The series is known for its ensemble cast, witty dialogue, and use of running gags. Arrested Development was critically acclaimed but had low ratings, and was canceled by Fox after three seasons. However, the show gained a cult following in syndication and on DVD, and was eventually revived for a fourth season on Netflix in 2013. The fifth and final season was released in 2019.

title: Christchurch, Dorset
text: Christchurch, Dorset, is a town and civil parish in the south of England. It is situated in the Bournemouth, Christchurch and Poole conurbation on the Dorset-Hampshire border and is the easternmost town in Dorset. Christchurch Priory dates back to the 11th century, and the town has a rich maritime history. Its harbourside area is popular with tourists, and the town is home to several museums and attractions, including Christchurch Castle and the Red House Museum and Gardens. Christchurch is also known for its beautiful beaches, including Mudeford Sandbank, which is accessible by ferry.

title: Shirley Manson
text: Shirley Ann Manson (born August 26, 1966) is a Scottish singer-songwriter. She is best known as the lead singer of the alternative rock band Garbage. Manson has also pursued a solo career, releasing her debut album, "Garbage", in 2006. She has collaborated with various artists, including The Prodigy, Moby, and Dave Grohl. Manson is known for her distinctive mezzo-soprano voice and introspective lyrics. She has received critical acclaim for her performances and songwriting, winning an Ivor Novello Award and several Grammy Award nominations.

title: Industrial Township, St. Louis County, Minnesota
text: Industrial Township is a township in St. Louis County, Minnesota, United States. The population was 359 at the 2020 census. It is located near the western end of Lake Superior, and the city of Duluth is about 7 miles (11 km) to the east. The township is home to the U.S. Steel plant, which is one of the largest steel mills in the United States. The plant employs about 1,200 people. Industrial Township is also home to the Iron Range Railroad Museum, which is a popular tourist destination.

title: Ironton, Wisconsin
text: Ironton is a village in Sauk County, Wisconsin, United States. The population was 131 at the 2010 census. The village is located on the Wisconsin River, and is home to the Ironton Ferry, which crosses the river to the town of Baraboo. Ironton is also the site of the former Ironton Charcoal Kilns, which were used to produce charcoal for use in iron furnaces.

title: Pedipalp
text: Pedipalp is a pair of appendages found in arachnids, such as spiders, scorpions, and horseshoe crabs. Pedipalps are located in front of the first pair of walking legs and are typically used for a variety of purposes, including grasping prey, sensing the environment, and reproduction. In some species, pedipalps are modified into chelicerae, which are used for injecting venom.

title: PFC CSKA Sofia
text: PFC CSKA Sofia, commonly known as CSKA or simply Army Men, is a Bulgarian professional football club based in Sofia, the capital of Bulgaria. Founded in 1948 as the central sports club of the Bulgarian Army, the club has won a record 31 national championships, 20 Bulgarian Cups, and 4 Bulgarian Supercups. CSKA plays its home matches at the Balgarska Armiya Stadium, which has a capacity of over 22,000 spectators. The club's traditional kit consists of red and white shirts, black shorts, and red socks.

title: Self-incompatibility
text: Self-incompatibility is a genetic mechanism that prevents self-fertilization in flowering plants. It ensures cross-pollination, promoting genetic diversity and increasing the chances of survival for the species. Self-incompatibility is controlled by a multi-allelic gene called the S-locus. Different alleles of the S-locus encode different proteins that interact to determine compatibility or incompatibility. When the pollen and stigma of a flower have the same S-alleles, self-incompatibility is triggered, inhibiting pollen tube growth and preventing fertilization.

title: Jacob Zuma
text: Jacob Gedleyihlekisa Zuma (born 12 April 1942) is a South African politician who served as the fourth President of South Africa from 2009 to 2018. He was the President of the African National Congress (ANC) from 2007 to 2017. Zuma was imprisoned on Robben Island for ten years during the apartheid era. After his release, he became a key figure in the ANC's negotiations with the apartheid government. Zuma has been a controversial figure throughout his career, with supporters praising his leadership and charisma, and critics accusing him of corruption and poor governance.

title: Genetically modified organism
text: A genetically modified organism (GMO) is a living organism whose genetic material has been altered using genetic engineering techniques. These techniques are used to transfer genes from one organism to another, resulting in an organism that has the characteristics of both organisms. GMOs are used to create organisms with desired traits, such as resistance to pests or herbicides, or increased nutritional value.

title: Waucedah Township, Michigan
text: Waucedah Township is a civil township of Dickinson County in the U.S. state of Michigan. The population was 919 at the 2010 census. The township was organized in 1881. It is named after Chief Waucedah of the Ottawa tribe. The township is located in the central part of the Upper Peninsula of Michigan, approximately 15 miles (24 km) south of the city of Iron Mountain. The main industry in the township is mining.

title: Wayland, Kentucky
text: Wayland, Kentucky, is an unincorporated community located in Floyd County, approximately 6 miles (9.7 kilometers) east of Prestonsburg. As of the 2010 census, the population of Wayland was 330. The community of Wayland was established in the late 19th century and was named after local landowner Wayland Pelfrey. Wayland primarily serves as a residential area for the surrounding communities and is home to several local businesses, including a post office, a grocery store, and a gas station.

title: Utica, Minnesota
text: Utica is an unincorporated community in Winona County, Minnesota, United States. It is located 10 miles (16 km) southwest of Winona, the county seat, and 9 miles (14 km) east of Altura. Utica was platted in 1855 and named after Utica, New York. The community once had a post office but it closed in 1975. Today, Utica is a small farming community with a population of around 50 people. It is home to a number of Amish and Mennonite families.

title: Sir George Trevelyan, 2nd Baronet
text: Sir George Trevelyan, 2nd Baronet, FBA (1838–1928) was a British Liberal politician and historian.
