Over its production run, the Riviera underwent several redesigns, but it always retained its distinctive long hood and short deck design. The Riviera was discontinued in 1999, but it remains a popular classic car today.

title: Bughouse chess
text: Bughouse chess is a variant of chess played on two boards simultaneously by four players in two teams of two. Each player controls their own board and pieces, with the objective of checkmating the opposing team's king. Players can capture pieces on either board and drop them onto their teammate's board as "bug moves." These captured pieces can then be used by the teammate to checkmate the opponent. Bughouse chess is known for its fast-paced, chaotic gameplay and requires excellent coordination and communication between teammates. It is a popular variant among experienced chess players and is often played in tournaments and online.

title: Chesapeake & Delaware Canal
text: The Chesapeake & Delaware Canal is a 14-mile (23 km) long, 450-foot (137 m) wide sea-level canal that connects the Delaware River with the Chesapeake Bay in the United States, allowing vessels to travel between the Atlantic Ocean and the Chesapeake Bay without having to navigate around the Delmarva Peninsula. It is the shortest, most direct route between Baltimore and Philadelphia, and the most important waterway linking the Port of Baltimore with the Port of Philadelphia and other ports on the Delaware River.

title: Paul Peter Ewald
text: Paul Peter Ewald (January 23, 1888 – August 22, 1985) was a German physicist. He is best known for his work on X-ray crystallography and for the Ewald sphere construction, which he developed in 1913. Ewald was born in Berlin, Germany, the son of two physicians. He studied mathematics and physics at the University of Berlin, graduating in 1910. He became a research associate at the University of Göttingen, where he worked under Max Born. Ewald's contributions to X-ray crystallography include the development of the Ewald sphere construction, which is used to visualize the diffraction of X-rays by crystals.

title: Politics of Estonia
text: Estonian politics take place in a framework of a parliamentary representative democratic republic, whereby the Prime Minister of Estonia is the head of government, and of a multi-party system. Executive power is exercised by the government. Legislative power is vested in both the government and Riigikogu. The judiciary is independent of the executive and the legislature. Estonia is a member state of the European Union and NATO.

title: Bray, County Wicklow
text: Bray is a coastal town in County Wicklow, Ireland. It is located approximately 20 kilometers south of Dublin. Bray has a population of around 32,000 people. The town is a popular tourist destination, with its sandy beach, Victorian promenade, and amusement park. Bray Head, a hill overlooking the town, is a popular hiking spot. The town is also home to a number of historical sites, including the ruins of a Norman castle and a medieval church.

title: Pascual Boing
text: Pascual Boing was a Spanish professional boxer who competed from 1926 to 1950. He held the Spanish middleweight title three times and the European middleweight title twice. Boing also challenged for the world middleweight title twice, but was unsuccessful both times. He was known for his aggressive fighting style and his powerful punches. Boing retired from boxing in 1950 with a record of 102 wins, 15 losses, and 2 draws. He was inducted into the International Boxing Hall of Fame in 2002.

title: Winfield, Kansas
text: Winfield is a city in and the county seat of Cowley County, Kansas, United States. The population was 4,644 at the 2020 census. Winfield is located in south-central Kansas, approximately 45 miles (72 km) southeast of Wichita. The city is situated on the Walnut River and is home to Winfield State Hospital and Southwestern College. Winfield is also known for its annual Walnut Valley Festival, which is one of the largest bluegrass and folk music festivals in the United States.

title: Juniata Township, Bedford County, Pennsylvania
text: Juniata Township is a township in Bedford County, Pennsylvania, United States. The population was 1,568 at the 2010 census. It is part of the Johnstown, Pennsylvania Metropolitan Statistical Area. Juniata Township is located in the eastern part of Bedford County and is bordered by Union Township to the north, East St. Clair Township to the east, Bedford Township to the south, and Southampton Township to the west. The main road through the township is U.S. Route 220.

title: International Church of the Foursquare Gospel
text: The International Church of the Foursquare Gospel is a Pentecostal Christian denomination founded in Los Angeles, California, in 1923 by Aimee Semple McPherson. The church is known for its emphasis on evangelism, missions, and social services. It has over 9 million members worldwide and operates in over 140 countries. The church's headquarters are located in Los Angeles, and its current leader is Bishop Jentezen Franklin.

title: Vitalism
text: Vitalism is the belief that living organisms are fundamentally different from non-living matter because they possess a vital force or essence that is not present in inanimate objects. This vital force is often described as a mysterious, non-physical entity that animates living beings and is responsible for their distinctive properties, such as growth, reproduction, and metabolism. Vitalism has been a prominent idea in biology since the time of Aristotle, but it declined in popularity during the 19th and 20th centuries as scientific advances provided increasingly convincing evidence for the reduction of biological phenomena to physical and chemical processes.

title: Music theory
text: Music theory encompasses the study and analysis of music's structure, elements, and principles. It involves understanding musical notation, scales, intervals, chords, harmony, rhythm, meter, and form. Music theorists analyze musical compositions to identify patterns, techniques, and relationships between elements. Music theory also explores the historical development of music, examining the evolution of styles, genres, and compositional practices. This knowledge provides insights into the underlying principles that govern music creation and enables musicians to communicate ideas and concepts effectively.

title: Courier 1B
text: Courier 1B was an American satellite launched on October 4, 1960, from Cape Canaveral, Florida. It was the second satellite in the Courier program, designed to test a store-and-forward communications system using delayed repeaters. Courier 1B was intended to relay voice, data, and facsimile messages between ground stations in the United States, Europe, and the Pacific. However, due to a technical malfunction, it failed to achieve its primary mission objectives.

title: Coachella, California
text: Coachella, California, is an unincorporated community in Riverside County. It is located in the Coachella Valley, approximately 25 miles (40 km) east of Palm Springs. The community is named after the Coachella Canal, which was built in the early 1900s to irrigate the valley. Coachella is a popular destination for tourists due to its warm climate and proximity to several national parks, including Joshua Tree National Park and Death Valley National Park. The community is also home to the Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival, which is held annually in April and attracts hundreds of thousands of people.

title: Bo Diddley
text: Bo Diddley (born Ellas McDaniel; December 30, 1928 – June 2, 2008) was an American singer, songwriter, and guitarist. He was a pioneer of rock and roll music, known for his distinctive beat and signature rectangular-shaped guitar. Diddley's music influenced numerous rock and roll, rhythm and blues, and hip-hop artists, including Elvis Presley, Buddy Holly, and the Rolling Stones. His songs "Bo Diddley" and "Who Do You Love?" are considered rock and roll classics. Diddley was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1986.

title: Road racing
text: Road racing encompasses motor races held on closed public roads, typically with temporary infrastructure such as barriers and grandstands. It is a challenging form of motorsport due to the unpredictable nature of the surfaces and the close proximity to obstacles. Notable examples include the Isle of Man TT, Macau Grand Prix, and Pikes Peak International Hill Climb. Road races offer unique spectator experiences and attract skilled riders who navigate the hazards of the courses at high speeds.

title: Malcolm Muggeridge
text: Malcolm Muggeridge (1903-1990) was a British journalist, satirist, and broadcaster. Known for his acerbic wit and incisive social commentary, he was a prominent figure in the intellectual and literary landscape of the 20th century. Muggeridge's career spanned decades, during which he worked for various newspapers and magazines, including the Daily Telegraph, The Observer, and The Spectator. He also served as editor of Punch magazine from 1953 to 1957. Throughout his writings and broadcasts, Muggeridge challenged conventional wisdom, questioned authority, and exposed hypocrisy in society. His work remains influential, offering a sharp and often satirical perspective on the challenges and absurdities of modern life.

title: Weekly World News
text: Weekly World News was an American tabloid newspaper published from 1979 to 2007. It was known for its sensationalistic and often bizarre headlines and stories, which often featured aliens, cryptids, and other paranormal phenomena. The newspaper was founded by Ed Anger, who had previously worked for the National Enquirer. Weekly World News was a popular success, with a circulation of over 1 million at its peak. However, it was also criticized for its lack of factual accuracy. The newspaper closed in 2007 due to declining circulation and the increasing popularity of online media.

title: Stanley Cohen (sociologist)
text: Stanley Cohen (born 1942) is a British sociologist best known for his work on youth subcultures, deviance, and moral panics. His 1972 book, "Folk Devils and Moral Panics," is considered a seminal work in the field of criminology. Cohen's research has shown how the media and the public can create perceptions of moral panic about certain groups or behaviors, leading to heightened social control and punishment. His work has influenced policy and practice in areas such as youth justice, drug control, and immigration. Cohen is a professor emeritus at the London School of Economics and Political Science.

title: Imp
text: Imp, in folklore and mythology, a mischievous or grotesque sprite or demon. Imps are typically depicted as small, winged creatures with a humanlike form and a long, pointed nose. They are said to be fond of playing pranks and causing trouble, and they are often associated with the devil or other evil spirits. The term "imp" is derived from the Middle English word "impe," which means "child" or "offspring." In some cultures, imps are believed to be the offspring of evil spirits, while in others they are said to be the souls of unbaptized children or those who died before they were baptized.

title: Edward Arthur Milne
text: Edward Arthur Milne (1896-1950) was an English astrophysicist and mathematician. He made significant contributions to the understanding of stellar atmospheres, radiative transfer, and cosmology. Milne developed the Milne model, which describes the absorption and scattering of light in a stellar atmosphere. He also developed the Milne-Eddington formula, which relates the mass of a star to its luminosity. Milne's work laid the foundation for much of modern astrophysics.

title: Kirby (character)
text: Kirby is a fictional character and the titular protagonist of the Kirby video game series. Created by Masahiro Sakurai, Kirby debuted in the 1992 Game Boy game Kirby's Dream Land. He is a pink, spherical creature with large, red feet and stubby arms. Kirby has the ability to inhale enemies and objects, copying their abilities and gaining their powers. He can also float and fly by puffing up his body. Kirby is known for his cheerful and innocent personality, and he often helps others in need. He is a popular character among gamers and has been featured in numerous spin-off games and other media.

title: Messier 87
text: Messier 87 (M87) is a supergiant elliptical galaxy located in the constellation Virgo. It is one of the most studied galaxies in the universe and is famous for hosting the first black hole to be imaged, known as M87*. M87 is a massive galaxy, with a diameter of about 120,000 light-years, and is the central galaxy of the Virgo Cluster. It has a prominent jet of material that extends for thousands of light-years from its center, which is powered by the accretion of gas onto M87*. M87 is an important object of study for astronomers, as it provides insights into the behavior of supermassive black holes and the formation of galaxies.

title: The Woodlanders
text: The Woodlanders is a novel by English writer Thomas Hardy, first published in 1887. Set in a remote woodland community in Dorset, England, the novel explores the clash between rural tradition and urban modernity, as well as the destructive power of passion. The story centers on Giles Winterborne, a young woodsman and skilled craftsman, who is torn between his love for Grace Melbury, a young woman from a wealthy family, and Marty South, a passionate and impulsive woman from the village. The novel's tragic conclusion underscores Hardy's belief in the inevitability of fate and the futility of resisting it.

title: Tokeland, Washington
text: Tokeland is an unincorporated community and census-designated place (CDP) in Pacific County, Washington, United States. The population was 158 at the 2010 census. Tokeland is located on the Long Beach Peninsula, approximately 15 miles (24 km) south of Ocean Shores. The community is known for its fishing and crabbing industry, as well as its beaches and other recreational opportunities.

title: M-6 (Michigan highway)
text: M-6 is a state trunkline highway in the Lower Peninsula of the US state of Michigan. The highway runs northwest–southeast for 281.563 miles (453.132 km) between US Highway 31 (US 31) in the village of Mackinaw City and the Indiana state line, where it continues south as State Road 1 (SR 1). M-6 passes through Mackinac County, Cheboygan County, Emmet County, Charlevoix County, Antrim County, Kalkaska County, Missaukee County, Wexford County, Lake County, Osceola County, Newaygo County, Muskegon County, Ottawa County, and Allegan County.

title: Telecommunications in Russia
text: Telecommunications in Russia has a long and rich history, dating back to the early days of the telegraph. Today, Russia has a modern and well-developed telecommunications infrastructure, with a high level of connectivity and access to a wide range of services. The country's telecommunications sector is dominated by a few large operators, including Rostelecom, MTS, and VimpelCom. Russia is also a major player in the global telecommunications market, with a number of its companies operating internationally.

title: Alan III, Duke of Brittany
text: Alan III, Duke of Brittany (1195 – 18 October 1221) was Duke of Brittany from 1203 until his death. He was the eldest son of Guy de Thouars, Viscount of Thouars and Constance, Duchess of Brittany. He succeeded his mother as duke at the age of eight. Alan's reign was marked by conflict with King John of England, who claimed suzerainty over Brittany. Alan was captured by John in 1206 and spent the next four years in captivity. After his release, Alan continued to resist English rule and allied with King Philip II of France. Alan died in battle against the English in 1221. He was succeeded by his son, Peter I.

title: Wish You Were Here (Pink Floyd album)
text: Wish You Were Here is the ninth studio album by the English progressive rock band Pink Floyd, released in September 1975. It was their first album since The Dark Side of the Moon (1973) and was recorded during a period of personal and creative turmoil for the band. The album's themes include alienation, absence, and the music industry. It features the hit singles "Have a Cigar" and "Wish You Were Here". The album received generally positive reviews and has been certified 6x platinum by the RIAA.

title: Texas Rangers (baseball)
text: The Texas Rangers are a professional baseball team based in Arlington, Texas. They are a member of the American League West division of Major League Baseball (MLB). The Rangers were founded in 1961 as the Washington Senators and moved to Arlington in 1972. They have won two American League pennants (2010, 2011) but have never won a World Series. The Rangers play their home games at Globe Life Field.

title: Music of the former Netherlands Antilles
text: The music of the former Netherlands Antilles, comprising the islands of Curaçao, Aruba, Bonaire, Sint Maarten, Sint Eustatius, and Saba, reflects the diverse cultural influences that have shaped the region's history. The traditional music of the islands often exhibits African, European, and Caribbean elements, with a heavy emphasis on percussion. Notable genres include tumba, a blend of African rhythms and Spanish melodies, and the march-like seú. Contemporary music from the former Netherlands Antilles includes genres such as reggae, hip hop, and Latin music, which have gained popularity in recent years. The music of the region continues to evolve, incorporating new influences while preserving its traditional roots.

title: Sicilian language
text: Sicilian is a Romance language spoken in Sicily, the Aeolian Islands, and parts of Calabria. It is a direct descendant of the Vulgar Latin spoken in Sicily during the Roman Empire, and has been influenced by various other languages throughout its history, including Greek, Arabic, and French. Sicilian has its own distinct grammar and vocabulary, and is not mutually intelligible with Italian. However, it is closely related to other Italo-Romance languages such as Neapolitan and Calabrian. Sicilian is spoken by around 5 million people, making it one of the most widely spoken minority languages in Europe.

title: Felidae
text: Felidae is a family of carnivorous mammals that includes cats, lions, tigers, leopards, and jaguars. Members of the Felidae family are characterized by their retractable claws, sharp teeth, and keen senses. They are typically solitary hunters that prey on a variety of animals, including rodents, birds, and fish. Felids are found in a wide range of habitats around the world, from tropical rainforests to deserts. Some species, such as the lion, are social animals that live in prides, while others, such as the tiger, are solitary.

title: Charles Osgood
text: Charles Osgood (born May 8, 1933) is an American television journalist and author. He is best known for hosting "CBS News Sunday Morning" from 1994 to 2016. Osgood began his career in journalism as a reporter for WKY-TV in Oklahoma City in 1957. He later worked for CBS News as a correspondent and anchor, and hosted the news magazine "60 Minutes II" from 1988 to 1994. Osgood is also an accomplished author, having written several books, including "The Osgood Files: Adventures in Reporting" (1998) and "See You on Sunday" (2013). He is known for his warm and engaging personality and his distinctive baritone voice.

title: Fat sand rat
text: The fat sand rat (Psammomys obesus) is a species of rodent in the family Muridae. It is found in arid and semi-arid regions of North Africa, particularly in Tunisia, Algeria, Libya, and Egypt. The fat sand rat is a small, stout rodent with a short, dense coat. It is mainly nocturnal and feeds on a variety of plants, fruits, and seeds. The fat sand rat is a social animal that lives in colonies of up to 100 individuals. It is a territorial animal that defends its territory from other colonies. The fat sand rat is not endangered, but its population is declining due to habitat loss and hunting.

title: List of Australian Leaders of the Opposition
text: The Leader of the Opposition is the leader of the largest political party that is not in government in Australia. The Leader of the Opposition is typically appointed by the Governor-General following a general election. The current Leader of the Opposition is Peter Dutton of the Liberal Party, since 2022.

title: Government House, Canberra
text: Government House, Canberra, is the official residence of the Governor-General of Australia. It is located in the suburb of Yarralumla, in the Australian Capital Territory. The house was designed by John Smith Murdoch and built between 1927 and 1930. It is a large, two-storey building with a hipped roof and a central portico. The house is surrounded by extensive gardens and grounds.

title: Peronism
text: Peronism is a political ideology based on the ideas of former Argentine President Juan Perón. It is a nationalist, populist movement that emphasizes social justice, economic equality, and political sovereignty. Peronism's central tenets include: A belief in a strong, centralized government that promotes economic development and social welfare. A commitment to social equality and the redistribution of wealth. A focus on national independence and self-determination. A strong emphasis on trade unionism and workers' rights. Peronism has been a major force in Argentine politics since the 1940s and continues to shape the country's political landscape today.

title: Bahram V
text: Bahram V, also known as Bahram Gur, was the Sassanian King of Kings of Iran from 420 to 438. He was the son and successor of Yazdegerd I. Bahram V was a skilled warrior and hunter, and his reign was marked by military victories and territorial expansion. He extended the Sassanian Empire eastward to the borders of India and westward to the Black Sea. Bahram V also patronized the arts and sciences, and his court was a center of learning and culture.

title: Prem Nazir
text: Prem Nazir, born Abdul Khader on April 7, 1926, was an Indian actor who predominantly worked in Malayalam cinema. Known as the "Evergreen Hero," he starred in over 700 films, making him one of the most prolific actors in Indian cinema history. Nazir's charismatic presence, versatility in portraying diverse characters, and natural acting style endeared him to audiences across generations. He received numerous accolades, including the Padma Bhushan, the third-highest civilian honor in India. Prem Nazir passed away on January 16, 1989, leaving an enduring legacy as one of the greatest actors in Malayalam cinema.

title: Welfare economics
text: Welfare economics is a branch of economics that focuses on the well-being of society as a whole. It uses economic theory and methods to evaluate the impact of government policies and other social interventions on the welfare of individuals and society. Welfare economics aims to identify and promote policies that improve the overall well-being of society, taking into account both economic efficiency and equity. Key concepts in welfare economics include Pareto efficiency, social welfare functions, and cost-benefit analysis. It is a valuable tool for policymakers and researchers seeking to design and evaluate policies that maximize societal well-being.

title: Telecommunications in Israel
text: Telecommunications in Israel has a long and rich history. The first telegraph line was established in 1855, connecting Jerusalem with Jaffa. The first telephone line was installed in 1881, between Jerusalem and Jericho. The first radio station was established in 1923, and the first television station was established in 1968. Currently, Israel has a modern and well-developed telecommunications infrastructure, including high-speed internet and mobile phone networks.

title: Liphistiidae
text: Liphistiidae is a family of spiders commonly called Liphistiids or primitive trapdoor spiders. They are a basal group of Mesothelae, the oldest spider suborder, and have a distribution range that extends from Southeast Asia to Japan. Liphistiids are fossorial spiders that inhabit burrows lined with silk, which they construct in the ground or under rocks. They are ambush predators that capture their prey using a trapdoor mechanism. Female Liphistiids are larger than males and can live for over 20 years.

title: Lei Feng
text: Lei Feng (March 18, 1940 – August 15, 1962) was a Chinese soldier who became a national icon and symbol of selfless service and modesty after his death. Known for his good deeds and his diary entries expressing his devotion to the Communist Party and his love for the Chinese people, Lei Feng is often cited as an example of the ideal communist citizen. His legacy continues to inspire volunteerism and acts of kindness throughout China.

title: University of Campinas
text: The University of Campinas (Unicamp) is a public research university in the state of São Paulo, Brazil. It was founded in 1966 and is one of the most prestigious universities in Latin America. Unicamp offers a wide range of undergraduate and graduate programs in the areas of science, technology, humanities, and social sciences. The university is known for its strong research output and has been ranked among the top 200 universities in the world by several international rankings. Unicamp is also a member of the Coimbra Group, a network of leading European and Latin American universities.

title: Stone Mountain, Georgia
text: Stone Mountain is a large granite dome monolith located about 16 miles (26 km) east of Atlanta, Georgia. It is the largest exposed granite batholith in the world, and is known for its iconic bas-relief carving of Confederate generals Robert E. Lee, Stonewall Jackson, and Jefferson Davis, which was created between 1923 and 1972. Stone Mountain Park, which encompasses the mountain and surrounding areas, is a popular tourist destination, offering a variety of activities including hiking, biking, camping, and laser shows.

title: Arthur de Gobineau
text: Arthur de Gobineau (1816-1882) was a French aristocrat, diplomat, and writer. He is best known for his theories on race, which he developed in his four-volume work Essai sur l'inégalité des races humaines (1853-1855). Gobineau believed that the Aryans were a superior race that had created all of the world's great civilizations. His theories were influential in the development of Nazi ideology and white supremacy. Gobineau also wrote novels and short stories, which are known for their exotic settings and their exploration of themes of love, race, and destiny.

title: Crawford County, Kansas
text: Crawford County, established in 1867 and named after former Kansas Governor Samuel J. Crawford, is located in the southeastern corner of Kansas. Covering an area of 594 square miles, it's known for its rich history in coal mining and agriculture. The county seat, Girard, is the largest city. Crawford County is bounded by Bourbon, Cherokee, Labette, and Neosho counties in Kansas, and by Missouri to the east and Oklahoma to the south. As of 2020, its population was estimated to be approximately 38,000.

title: Marcus Furius Camillus
text: Marcus Furius Camillus (c. 446–365 BC) was a Roman statesman and military leader who played a prominent role in the early history of the Roman Republic. He was a five-time consular tribune and is considered one of Rome's greatest generals. Camillus is best known for his victory over the Gauls in 390 BC at the Battle of the Allia. He was also responsible for the conquest of Veii in 396 BC and the capture of Rome from the Gauls in 390 BC. Camillus's military successes earned him the title of "second founder of Rome".

title: Cashmere, Washington
text: Cashmere is a city in Chelan County, Washington, United States. The population was 3,060 at the 2010 census. Cashmere is located in the Wenatchee Valley, about 10 miles (16 km) southeast of Wenatchee. The city is named after the soft, luxurious fabric made from the wool of the cashmere goat. Cashmere is a major agricultural center, and its economy is based on the production of apples, cherries, and other fruits. The city is also home to several wineries and breweries.

title: Lucinda Williams
text: Lucinda Williams is an American singer-songwriter known for her distinctive vocals and introspective lyrics. Born in Lake Charles, Louisiana, in 1953, she emerged as a critically acclaimed artist in the early 1990s with albums like "Sweet Old World" and "Car Wheels on a Gravel Road." Williams' music often explores themes of love, loss, and the complexities of human relationships. Her songs have been covered by artists such as Bob Dylan, Emmylou Harris, and Tom Petty. In 2020, she was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.

title: Sarojini Naidu
text: Sarojini Naidu, the "Nightingale of India," was a prominent poet, political activist, and women's rights advocate. Born in 1879 in Hyderabad, she became the first Indian woman to hold a presidential position, serving as the Congress president in 1925. Naidu's poetry, often inspired by Indian mythology and folklore, explored themes of love, nature, and nationalism. Her political activism focused on the Indian independence movement, particularly the rights of women and the oppressed. Naidu's powerful speeches and eloquent writings contributed significantly to India's struggle for freedom.

title: Oku Yasukata
text: Oku Yasukata (奥保鞏, 1847–1910) was a Japanese general who served in the Imperial Japanese Army. He is best known for his command of the Japanese forces during the Russo-Japanese War. Oku led the Japanese to victory in the Battle of Mukden, which was one of the largest and most decisive battles of the war. After the war, Oku served as governor-general of Korea from 1910 until his death in 1911.

title: Military academy
text: A military academy is an educational institution that prepares individuals for service as officers in the armed forces. These academies provide a rigorous curriculum that combines military training with academic coursework in subjects such as history, political science, and leadership. Graduates of military academies are commissioned as officers and typically serve in leadership roles within their respective branches. Military academies play a vital role in developing future military leaders. They provide a unique blend of practical experience and theoretical knowledge that prepares graduates to effectively command and lead troops.

title: Blish lock
text: The Blish lock is a type of cryptographic device that allows a one-time pad to be securely generated between two parties. It was developed by James Blish, an American science fiction writer and editor, in the 1940s. The Blish lock consists of two identical devices, each of which contains a set of numbered keys. To generate a one-time pad, each party selects a key from their device and then uses the numbers on the keys to create a random sequence of characters. The two parties then exchange their key numbers and use the same sequence of characters to create the one-time pad.

title: Scientific realism
text: Scientific realism is a philosophical position that holds that the entities and theories of science accurately describe reality. Proponents of scientific realism argue that science provides us with the best possible understanding of the universe, and that scientific knowledge is objective and reliable. Scientific realism is often contrasted with instrumentalism, which holds that scientific theories are merely tools for making predictions, and do not necessarily describe reality. Instrumentalist argue that scientific knowledge is provisional and subject to change, and that it is not possible to know whether scientific theories are true or false.

title: Fnord
text: Fnord is a fictional word or concept used as an example of a subliminal message or meme that is alleged to be surreptitiously embedded in media and culture to influence thoughts and behavior. The term originated in the 1960s and has been used in various works of fiction, including the Illuminatus! trilogy by Robert Shea and Robert Anton Wilson. The concept of Fnord suggests that hidden messages or ideas can be implanted in the subconscious mind through seemingly innocuous channels, such as advertising, news, or popular entertainment. These messages are said to be designed to subtly manipulate and control individuals without their conscious awareness.

title: Holocaust theology
text: Holocaust theology examines the religious and philosophical implications of the Holocaust. It grapples with questions about the existence and nature of God, the problem of evil, and the meaning of human suffering. Holocaust theologians have proposed various responses to these existential questions, some arguing for a radical reinterpretation of traditional religious beliefs, while others seek to find meaning and hope in the face of such profound tragedy.

title: Colstrip, Montana
text: Colstrip, Montana, is a town located in southeastern Montana, United States. It is situated in Garfield County and has a population of around 2,200 people. Colstrip is primarily known for its coal mining industry, with several coal mines operating in the surrounding area. The town is home to the Colstrip Power Plant, one of the largest coal-fired power plants in the United States. Colstrip also has a rich history, with evidence of human habitation dating back to the Clovis culture. The town was officially founded in 1924 and named after E.H. "Colonel" Cooney, a mine superintendent.

title: Santa Cruz Province, Argentina
text: Santa Cruz Province is the southernmost and second-largest province in Argentina. It borders Chile to the west, the Atlantic Ocean to the east, and the provinces of Chubut to the north and Tierra del Fuego, Antarctica, and the South Atlantic Islands to the south. The province has a population of about 300,000 people and its capital is Río Gallegos. The province is known for its vast and sparsely populated landscapes, including the Patagonian steppes, the Andes Mountains, and the Perito Moreno Glacier.

title: Stephanie McMahon
text: Stephanie McMahon is an American businesswoman, professional wrestler, and occasional actress. She is the Chief Brand Officer of WWE and appears regularly on its television programming. McMahon is the daughter of WWE Chairman and CEO Vince McMahon and Linda McMahon. She began her career in WWE as a ring announcer in 1999. In the early 2000s, she transitioned to an on-screen role as a villainous character, known for her manipulative and ruthless tactics. McMahon has held various championships in WWE, including the Women's Championship and the Raw Women's Championship.

title: Backward chaining
text: Backward chaining is a problem-solving method that starts with a goal and works backward to identify the steps needed to achieve it. It is often used in artificial intelligence and other fields where complex problems need to be solved. The process of backward chaining begins by defining the goal and then breaking it down into smaller sub-goals. Each sub-goal is then further refined until they can be broken down no more and become actions. Backward chaining can be a powerful problem-solving tool, as it allows complex problems to be broken down into smaller, more manageable steps.

497 (CDXCVII) was a common year starting on Thursday of the Julian calendar. At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Anastasius II and Rufus (or, less frequently, year 1250 Ab urbe condita). The denomination 497 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.

title: Vehicle registration plate
text: A vehicle registration plate, also known as a license plate, number plate, or licence plate, is a metal or plastic plate attached to a motor vehicle or trailer for official identification purposes. The registration plate is issued by the relevant government authority and displays a unique combination of letters and numbers that identifies the vehicle. Registration plates are used to track vehicle ownership, enforce traffic laws, and facilitate toll collection and car park access. They also provide a means of identifying stolen vehicles and tracking down criminals.

title: Animation
text: Animation is the art of creating movement and shape changes in inanimate objects. It is used in film, television, video games, and other media. There are many different types of animation, including hand-drawn, computer-generated, and stop-motion. Animation can be used to create a wide range of effects, from realistic to abstract. It can be used to tell stories, entertain, or educate. Animation is a powerful tool that can be used to communicate ideas and emotions in a unique and engaging way.

title: Softball
text: Softball, a derivative of baseball, is a team sport where two teams of nine players each take turns batting and fielding. Using a larger ball than baseball and a smaller diamond, the game is played on a field with four bases: home plate, first base, second base, and third base. The objective of softball is for the batting team to score runs by hitting the ball and advancing around the bases without being caught out. The fielding team attempts to prevent the batters from reaching base by catching or fielding the ball.

title: Slavery
text: Slavery is a system in which one person, known as the slave, is owned by another person, known as the master. The master has complete control over the slave's life and can force them to do whatever they want. Slavery has existed for centuries in many different cultures and societies. It was once common in Europe and Africa, but it was eventually abolished in most countries. However, slavery still exists in some parts of the world today.

title: Anchor Point, Alaska
text: Anchor Point is an unincorporated community in the Kenai Peninsula Borough, Alaska, United States. It is located on the west side of Cook Inlet, approximately 20 miles (32 km) south of Homer. The community's primary industries are fishing and tourism. Anchor Point is home to the Anchor River, a popular destination for salmon fishing; Halibut Cove, a small fishing community located on the east side of the community; and the Anchor Point State Recreation Area, which offers camping, hiking, and wildlife viewing opportunities.

title: Pete Sampras
text: Pete Sampras, an American former professional tennis player, is widely considered one of the greatest tennis players of all time. Born in Washington, D.C., Sampras rose to prominence in the early 1990s and dominated the sport for a decade. Throughout his illustrious career, he won 14 Grand Slam singles titles, including a record seven Wimbledon championships. With his powerful serve-and-volley game, Sampras became known for his aggressive style of play and unwavering determination on the court. He retired in 2002 and was inducted into the International Tennis Hall of Fame in 2007.

title: Alfred Sant
text: Alfred Sant (born 28 February 1948) is a Maltese politician who served as Prime Minister of Malta from 1996 to 1998. A member of the Labour Party, he was Leader of the Opposition from 1992 to 2008 and again from 2013 to 2017. He was also a Member of the European Parliament (MEP) from 2009 to 2013. Sant is a medical doctor by profession. He studied medicine at the University of Malta and specialized in internal medicine. He worked as a physician at St. Luke's Hospital in Gwardamangia.

title: South Nyack, New York
text: South Nyack is a village in the town of Orangetown, Rockland County, New York, United States. It is situated on the west bank of the Hudson River, approximately 20 miles (32 km) north of New York City. As of the 2020 census, the village had a population of 3,615. Notable landmarks in South Nyack include Edward Hopper House Art Center, home to the artist Edward Hopper, and St. John's Episcopal Church, a historic church dating back to the 18th century. The village is served by the South Nyack station on the Metro-North Railroad's Hudson Line.

title: Peter the Painter
text: Peter the Painter, a moniker attributed to various individuals throughout history, has become synonymous with anarchist assassins. One notable figure known as Peter the Painter was Johann Most, a German-American anarchist who advocated for violence and revolution. Most, using the alias Peter the Painter, was implicated in the Haymarket affair in Chicago in 1886, where a bomb exploded during a labor rally, killing several people. Most's involvement in the incident led to his imprisonment and eventual exile from the United States. The use of "Peter the Painter" as a pseudonym underscores the secrecy and anonymity often associated with anarchist movements.

title: Brazilian Armed Forces
text: The Brazilian Armed Forces (Portuguese: Forças Armadas Brasileiras) is the military force of Brazil. It is composed of the Brazilian Army, Brazilian Navy, Brazilian Air Force, and Brazilian Marine Corps. The Brazilian Armed Forces are responsible for defending the nation against external threats and maintaining internal order. They have participated in numerous peacekeeping missions around the world, including the United Nations Mission in Haiti and the United Nations Stabilization Mission in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.

title: Halva
text: Halva is a popular Middle Eastern dessert typically made from tahini, sugar, and nuts. It has a dense, crumbly texture and a sweet, nutty flavor. Halva can be made with various nuts, such as pistachios, almonds, or walnuts, and can also be flavored with spices like cinnamon or cardamom. Halva is believed to have originated in the Middle East and has been enjoyed for centuries. It is a popular dessert during Ramadan and other holidays. Halva can be found in various forms, including bars, slices, or balls, and is often served with tea or coffee.

title: Samuel Mazzuchelli
text: Samuel Charles Mazzuchelli (November 4, 1806 – February 23, 1864) was an Italian-born American Catholic priest and missionary. He established the first permanent Catholic mission in Wisconsin, and was the first bishop of the Diocese of Milwaukee. Mazzuchelli was born in Milan, Italy, and ordained a priest in 1829. He came to the United States in 1830, and spent the next 34 years as a missionary in the Midwest. He established missions in Wisconsin, Illinois, Iowa, and Minnesota, and was instrumental in the growth of the Catholic Church in the region.

title: Max Stirner
text: Max Stirner, born Johann Kaspar Schmidt, was a German philosopher known for his radical individualism and anarchism. His most famous work, "The Ego and Its Own," challenged traditional notions of the state, morality, and religion. Stirner rejected all forms of external authority, arguing that the individual's own self-interest and desires should be paramount. His philosophy, often referred to as "egoism," influenced later anarchist thinkers such as Friedrich Nietzsche and the anti-capitalist movement.

title: Eurofighter Typhoon
text: The Eurofighter Typhoon is a twin-engine, canard-delta wing, multirole fighter aircraft, developed and built by a consortium of Airbus, BAE Systems, and Leonardo. The Typhoon is designed to be a highly agile and effective air superiority fighter, with advanced avionics and weapons systems. It is also capable of carrying out a variety of other roles, including ground attack, maritime strike, and reconnaissance. The Typhoon has been in service with the air forces of several European countries since 2003, and has been used in combat operations in Libya and Syria.

title: Edward Lasker
text: Edward Lasker (December 3, 1885 – March 25, 1981) was a German-American chess master and author. He won the Western Chess Association championship in 1909 and tied for first in the 1911 New York State Championship. Lasker was also a prominent chess journalist and organizer, serving as editor of the American Chess Bulletin from 1911 to 1947. In 1916, Lasker played a famous game against José Raúl Capablanca, which Capablanca won with a brilliant queen sacrifice. Lasker retired from tournament chess in 1924 but continued to write and lecture on the game. He was inducted into the World Chess Hall of Fame in 2001.

title: Respiratory system
text: The respiratory system is a system of organs that work together to get oxygen into the body and remove carbon dioxide. The main organs of the respiratory system are the lungs, which are located in the chest. The lungs are made up of millions of tiny air sacs called alveoli. The alveoli are where oxygen from the air enters the bloodstream. The respiratory system also includes the nose, mouth, pharynx, larynx, trachea, and bronchi. These structures help to move air in and out of the lungs.

title: Outer Plane
text: The Outer Plane is a theoretical concept in cosmology that describes a hypothetical region beyond the observable universe. This realm is often theorized as existing outside the laws of physics and the constraints of space-time as we know them. The Outer Plane is often associated with abstract concepts such as the origin of the universe, the afterlife, or the nature of consciousness. Some scientific theories suggest that the Outer Plane may be a higher-dimensional space or a separate dimension altogether. However, due to its speculative nature, the existence and characteristics of the Outer Plane remain a subject of ongoing scientific debate and philosophical inquiry.

title: Stockholm
text: Stockholm, the capital of Sweden, is a vibrant and historic city built on 14 islands, offering a unique blend of medieval charm and modern sophistication. Known for its stunning waterways and picturesque architecture, Stockholm is a major cultural and economic hub, boasting world-renowned museums, galleries, and theaters. With a rich history dating back to the 13th century, the city is home to iconic landmarks such as the Royal Palace, Gamla Stan (the Old Town), and the Vasa Museum, housing the preserved 17th-century warship Vasa. Stockholm is also renowned for its commitment to sustainability, with an extensive public transportation system and a focus on green living.

title: Tribute act
text: A tribute act is a live musical performance that imitates the style and repertoire of a particular music artist or band. Tribute acts often perform at festivals, clubs, and other live music venues. Some tribute acts aim to recreate the original artist's sound and stage presence as accurately as possible, while others take a more creative approach, reinterpreting the artist's music in their own unique style. Tribute acts can be a popular form of entertainment for fans of the original artist, as they offer a chance to experience the artist's music live without having to see the actual artist in person.

title: Equality feminism
text: Equality feminism is a branch of feminism that advocates for political, economic, and social equality of the sexes. It emerged in the 19th and early 20th centuries as part of the first wave of feminism. Equality feminists believe that women and men should have the same rights and opportunities in all areas of life, including education, employment, politics, and family life. They argue that the traditional gender roles and expectations that have historically disadvantaged women should be challenged and eliminated.

title: Günter Netzer
text: Günter Netzer (born September 14, 1944) is a German former footballer. A midfielder known for his exceptional passing ability and vision, Netzer played for Borussia Mönchengladbach, Real Madrid, and the West German national team. With Borussia Mönchengladbach, Netzer won the Bundesliga five times and the UEFA Cup in 1975. He also led the club to the European Cup final in 1977. With Real Madrid, he won the La Liga title in 1979. Netzer played 37 times for West Germany, scoring six goals. He was a member of the team that won the 1974 FIFA World Cup and finished second in the 1972 UEFA European Championship.

title: Pangolin
text: Pangolins are solitary, nocturnal mammals covered in protective scales made of keratin. They have long, slender bodies with short legs and a long, muscular tail. Pangolins have poor eyesight and hearing, but their sense of smell is highly developed. They are found in tropical and subtropical regions of Africa and Asia. Pangolins are insectivores and their main diet consists of ants and termites. They use their long, sticky tongue to capture their prey. Pangolins are shy and elusive animals and are rarely seen in the wild. They are an important part of the ecosystem, as they help to control the population of ants and termites.

title: Sharpsburg, Pennsylvania
text: Sharpsburg is a borough in Allegheny County, Pennsylvania, United States. It is located on the north bank of the Allegheny River, opposite the city of Pittsburgh. As of the 2020 census, the borough had a population of 3,442. Sharpsburg was founded in 1832 by James Sharp, a prominent local businessman. The borough was originally named Jamestown, but its name was changed to Sharpsburg in 1871. Sharpsburg is best known as the site of the Battle of Antietam, which was fought on September 17, 1862. The battle was a turning point in the Civil War, and it marked the end of Confederate General Robert E. Lee's first invasion of the North.

title: Mehdi Ghezali
text: Mehdi Ghezali (born 1981) is an Algerian footballer who plays as a striker for CR Belouizdad in the Algerian Ligue Professionnelle 1. He began his career with MC Alger in 1999 and has since played for several clubs in Algeria, Tunisia, and Saudi Arabia. He has also represented Algeria at international level, making 15 appearances and scoring 2 goals. Ghezali is a prolific goalscorer, having scored over 100 goals in his club career. He is known for his pace, strength, and ability to score goals from close range.

title: Pepperdine University
text: Pepperdine University is a private, nonprofit Christian university in Malibu, California. Founded in 1937, it is affiliated with the Churches of Christ. Pepperdine offers undergraduate and graduate programs through its Seaver College of Letters, Arts, and Sciences; the Graziadio School of Business and Management; the School of Public Policy; the Caruso School of Law; and the Graduate School of Education and Psychology. The university has over 8,000 students and maintains an endowment of over $600 million. Pepperdine is known for its strong academics, beautiful campus, and commitment to community service.

title: Bruce Fairbairn
text: Bruce Fairbairn (1949–1999) was a Canadian record producer and audio engineer best known for his work on albums by Bon Jovi, AC/DC, Blue Öyster Cult, Chicago, and Poison. He was also a member of the Canadian rock band, The Guess Who. Fairbairn's production style was characterized by its big, live sound, with an emphasis on strong melodies and powerful hooks. He was also known for his ability to create a cohesive sound from a variety of musical influences. Fairbairn died of a heart attack in 1999 at the age of 50. He was posthumously inducted into the Canadian Music Hall of Fame in 2009.

title: Bow River
text: The Bow River is a major river in Alberta, Canada. It is the largest tributary of the South Saskatchewan River and is part of the Saskatchewan River Basin. The Bow River originates in the Rocky Mountains and flows east through the Canadian Rockies and foothills, eventually joining the South Saskatchewan River near Saskatoon. The river is approximately 587 km long and has a drainage basin of 26,280 km².

title: Tudor Vladimirescu
text: Tudor Vladimirescu (c. 1780–1821) was a Romanian revolutionary leader who organized an uprising against the Phanariot rule in Wallachia. He led a force of peasants and boyars in a short-lived revolt against the Ottoman Empire, demanding autonomy for Wallachia and the restoration of traditional rights. Despite initial successes, Vladimirescu's rebellion was crushed, and he was captured and executed by Ottoman forces. His uprising paved the way for the Romanian Revolution of 1848 and is considered a formative event in Romanian history.

title: Populuxe
text: Populuxe, a portmanteau of popular and deluxe, was a design aesthetic and cultural movement that emerged in the United States in the late 1940s and lasted until the mid-1960s. It was characterized by a vibrant, optimistic, and futuristic design style that reflected the economic prosperity and technological advancements of the postwar era. Populuxe embraced new materials, such as plastics and aluminum, and incorporated bold colors, geometric shapes, and streamlined forms into its designs. The movement extended beyond consumer products, influencing architecture, home decor, advertising, and even popular culture.

title: W. A. C. Bennett
text: W. A. C. Bennett (1900–1979) was a Canadian politician who served as the 25th premier of British Columbia from 1952 to 1972. A member of the Social Credit Party, he was known for his conservative policies and his focus on economic development. During his time in office, Bennett oversaw the construction of several major infrastructure projects, including the W. A. C. Bennett Dam and the British Columbia Place Stadium. His legacy remains controversial, with some praising his achievements while others criticize his authoritarian tendencies and his impact on the province's environment.

title: Peter Atkins
text: Peter William Atkins, born June 10, 1940, is a British chemist and writer. He is known for his contributions to inorganic chemistry and for his popular science books, which have sold over 10 million copies worldwide. Atkins has written over 50 books, including "Inorganic Chemistry," "Physical Chemistry," and "Galileo's Finger." He has also written several books for the general public, such as "The Periodic Kingdom" and "The Elements." Atkins has received numerous awards for his work, including the Royal Society of Chemistry's Faraday Medal and the American Chemical Society's Priestley Medal.

title: History of anime
text: The history of anime dates back to the early 20th century, with the release of the first animated short film in Japan in 1917. In the 1960s and 1970s, anime began to gain international popularity, thanks to the work of directors such as Osamu Tezuka, Hayao Miyazaki, and Mamoru Oshii. Today, anime is a global phenomenon, with fans of all ages around the world.

title: Pacheco, California
text: Pacheco is an unincorporated community and census-designated place (CDP) in Contra Costa County, California, United States. It is named after Romualdo Pacheco, a California state legislator. Pacheco was originally a stagecoach stop on the road between San Francisco and Sacramento. Today, it is a bedroom community for the San Francisco Bay Area. As of the 2020 census, the population of the CDP was 3,888.

title: Iván Rodríguez
text: Iván Rodríguez, nicknamed "Pudge", is a Puerto Rican former professional baseball catcher who played 21 seasons in Major League Baseball (MLB). A 14-time All-Star, Rodríguez won 13 Gold Glove Awards, a Silver Slugger Award, and the American League Most Valuable Player Award in 1999. He is widely regarded as one of the greatest catchers in MLB history. Rodríguez was born in Manatí, Puerto Rico, and signed with the Texas Rangers as an international free agent in 1990. He made his MLB debut with the Rangers in 1991 and played for them until 2002. He also played for the Florida Marlins, Detroit Tigers, New York Yankees, Houston Astros, and Washington Nationals.

title: Gabriel Marcel
text: Gabriel Marcel (1889–1973) was a French philosopher, dramatist, and music critic. He was one of the founders of existentialism, and his work has been influential in the fields of philosophy, theology, and literature. Marcel's philosophy is centered on the concept of being, which he understood as a dynamic and participatory process. He argued that being is not something that can be fully grasped by the intellect, but rather must be experienced through concrete situations and relationships. Marcel also emphasized the importance of love and freedom, and he maintained that human beings are called to transcend themselves and to participate in a higher reality.

title: Or Akiva
text: Or Akiva (c. 50–135 CE) was a central figure in the development of early Rabbinic Judaism. He is best known for his contributions to the Mishnah, a collection of Jewish law, and for his leadership role in the Bar Kokhba revolt against Roman rule. Akiva was a disciple of Rabbi Akiva ben Yosef and was himself a teacher of Rabbi Shimon bar Yochai. He is considered one of the most important sages in Jewish history and is often referred to as "Rabbi Akiva the Great."

title: Memorial Day
text: Memorial Day, formerly known as Decoration Day, is a federal holiday in the United States observed every year on the last Monday in May. It commemorates the men and women who died while serving in the United States Armed Forces. The holiday originated after the American Civil War, when various groups of citizens began decorating the graves of fallen soldiers with flowers and flags. In 1868, General John A. Logan declared May 30 as the official Decoration Day, and it was later renamed Memorial Day in 1967. Today, Memorial Day is a day for Americans to remember and honor those who died in service to their country. It is a day for parades, speeches, and other ceremonies, as well as a time for families to visit the graves of their loved ones.

title: ARP spoofing
text: ARP spoofing, also known as ARP poisoning, is a technique used in computer networks to intercept and manipulate traffic. By sending malicious Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) messages, an attacker can associate their own Media Access Control (MAC) address with the IP address of another device on the network, allowing them to intercept or even modify traffic intended for that device. ARP spoofing is often used in conjunction with other attacks, such as man-in-the-middle attacks, to gain unauthorized access to sensitive information or control network traffic.

title: Reference counting
text: Reference counting is a memory management technique that keeps track of the number of references to an object. When the count reaches zero, the object can be safely deleted. This technique is often used in programming languages with automatic memory management, such as Python, Ruby, and Java. Reference counting is relatively simple to implement, but it can be inefficient in some cases. For example, if an object is referenced by a large number of other objects, it can take a long time to delete the object when all of the references are gone.

title: Dynamic mechanical analysis
text: Dynamic mechanical analysis (DMA) is a technique used to study the viscoelastic properties of materials. It involves applying a sinusoidal force or displacement to a sample and measuring the resulting stress or strain. The frequency and amplitude of the applied force can be varied to probe the material's response over a wide range of conditions. DMA can be used to characterize the stiffness, damping, and energy storage properties of materials, as well as their transitions between different states, such as the glass transition or melting point.

title: General Mobile Radio Service
text: General Mobile Radio Service (GMRS) is a personal, two-way radio service intended for recreational and non-commercial use. It is regulated by the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) in the United States and by Industry Canada in Canada. GMRS operates on UHF frequencies in the 460–462 MHz range, and has a maximum power output of 5 watts. GMRS users must obtain a license from the FCC or Industry Canada, and must pass a simple test.

title: OK Computer
text: OK Computer is the third studio album by the English rock band Radiohead, released on 21 May 1997. It was produced by the band and Nigel Godrich. The album was a critical and commercial success, reaching number one in the UK and number two in the US. It has been widely acclaimed as one of the greatest albums of the 1990s and of all time. OK Computer is a concept album that explores themes of alienation, isolation, and technology. The music is characterized by its experimental and electronic sound, which incorporates elements of ambient music, Krautrock, and classical music. The album's lyrics are often cryptic and allusive, but they generally deal with themes of personal and societal collapse.

title: Louin, Mississippi
text: Louin is an unincorporated community located in Jasper County, Mississippi, United States. It is situated along Mississippi Highway 15, approximately 10 miles (16 km) east of Bay Springs and 12 miles (19 km) west of Heidelberg. Louin has a post office with the ZIP code 39451. The community was established in the late 1800s and was named after Louin Day, a local landowner. Louin has a small population and is primarily a farming community. The main crops grown in the area include soybeans, corn, and cotton.

title: Shinsaibashi
text: Shinsaibashi is a vibrant shopping and entertainment district in the heart of Osaka, Japan. Known for its bustling atmosphere and diverse offerings, it stretches from Shinsaibashi Station in the south to Namba Station in the north. The district is a shopper's paradise, with a wide range of retail stores, department stores, and boutiques catering to all tastes. Visitors can also enjoy a variety of restaurants, cafes, and bars, as well as entertainment options such as cinemas, arcades, and live music venues. The area is particularly popular during the evening hours, when the streets come alive with neon lights and throngs of people.

title: The Destiny of The Mother Church
text: The Destiny of The Mother Church is a sculpture by Harry Bertoia created in 1950. It is located in the Christian Science Center in Boston, Massachusetts. The sculpture is made of welded bronze and is approximately 9 feet tall. The Destiny of The Mother Church is a non-representational sculpture that consists of a series of intertwining curves and spirals. The sculpture has been interpreted as a symbol of the growth and evolution of the Christian Science movement.

title: Paul Graham (programmer)
text: Paul Graham is a British-American computer scientist, essayist, venture capitalist, and co-founder of the startup incubator Y Combinator. He is known for his essays on computer science, startups, and the future of technology. Graham was born in England and studied at Cambridge University. After graduating, he worked at Symbolics, a Lisp machine company. In 1995, he co-founded Viaweb, one of the first web application frameworks. Viaweb was acquired by Yahoo! in 1998. In 2005, Graham and Jessica Livingston co-founded Y Combinator, a startup incubator that has funded and mentored thousands of startups.

title: Agostinho Neto
text: Agostinho Neto was an Angolan poet, physician, and politician. He was the first president of Angola, serving from 1975 until his death in 1979. Neto was a leading figure in the Angolan independence movement, and his poetry played a significant role in inspiring the struggle for liberation. As president, he oversaw the country's transition to independence and implemented socialist policies. Neto died in Moscow at the age of 56.

title: National Association of Colored Women's Clubs
text: The National Association of Colored Women's Clubs (NACWC) is an African-American women's organization in the United States. It was founded in 1896 by a group of prominent black women, including Mary McLeod Bethune and Ida B. Wells-Barnett. The NACWC's mission is to promote the advancement of African-American women and their families through education, advocacy, and service. The organization has been involved in a wide range of social and political issues, including civil rights, education, health care, and economic development. Today, the NACWC has over 300,000 members in 40 states and the District of Columbia.

title: Lynchburg, Tennessee
text: Lynchburg is a town in Moore County, Tennessee, United States. The population was 636 at the 2010 census. Lynchburg is located in the south-central part of the state, approximately 50 miles (80 km) southeast of Nashville. The town is situated on the Elk River and is surrounded by rolling hills and farmland. Lynchburg is known for its many distilleries, including the Jack Daniel's Distillery, which is the oldest registered distillery in the United States.

title: Ellendale, Minnesota
text: Ellendale is a city in Steele County, Minnesota, United States. The population was 684 at the 2010 census. It is part of the Mankato-North Mankato Metropolitan Statistical Area. Ellendale was incorporated in 1868. The city is home to Ellendale High School, which serves students in grades 9-12. Ellendale is also home to the Ellendale Opera House, which hosts a variety of events throughout the year. The city is located on the Cannon River and is surrounded by farmland.

title: EarthBound
text: "EarthBound", released in Japan as "Mother 2: Gyiyg Strikes Back!", is a role-playing video game developed by Ape Inc. and HAL Laboratory, and published by Nintendo for the Super Nintendo Entertainment System. It was released in Japan in 1994 and in North America in 1995. The game is the second installment in the "Mother" series, following "Mother" (also known as "EarthBound Zero") for the Famicom. "EarthBound" follows the story of Ness, a young boy who must travel across the United States to defeat the alien Giygas and save the world. Along the way, he is joined by a group of friends, including Paula, Jeff, and Poo. The game is known for its unique setting, quirky characters, and memorable story.

title: Taipei Metro
text: Taipei Metro, previously known as the Taipei MRT, is a rapid transit system serving Taipei and New Taipei City in Taiwan. It is operated by the Taipei Rapid Transit Corporation (TRTC) and consists of six lines, with a total length of 131.1 kilometers (81.5 miles) and 117 stations. The system is known for its efficiency, cleanliness, and modern facilities, and is widely regarded as one of the best metro systems in the world. It plays a vital role in the transportation network of Taipei, connecting major districts, business centers, and tourist attractions.

title: Sunshine, Victoria
text: Sunshine is a suburb of Melbourne, Victoria, Australia, 12 km west of the Melbourne CBD. Its local government area is the City of Brimbank. At the 2021 census, Sunshine had a population of 10,135. The area was first settled in the 1850s and was originally known as Little River. In 1887, the name was changed to Sunshine due to the abundance of sunshine in the area. The suburb developed rapidly in the early 20th century, with the establishment of factories and warehouses. Today, Sunshine is a diverse and vibrant suburb with a strong sense of community. It is home to a range of shops, restaurants, and cafes, as well as a number of schools and parks. Sunshine is also well-connected to the rest of Melbourne by public transport.

title: M-8 (Michigan highway)
text: M-8 is a state trunkline highway in the US state of Michigan that runs north–south in the Lower Peninsula. The highway runs 240.742 miles (387.437 km) from the Indiana state line south of Niles to US 2 east of St. Ignace. M-8 crosses the Straits of Mackinac via the Mackinac Bridge. The highway was first designated in the 1919 Michigan State Highway Department report as a route from the Indiana state line to Mackinac City.

title: Porcupine, South Dakota
text: Porcupine, South Dakota, is an unincorporated community located in Shannon County. It is situated near the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation and is home to a predominantly Native American population. The community's name is derived from the nearby Porcupine Creek, which was named after the numerous porcupines found in the area. Porcupine is a small community with limited amenities, but it is known for its scenic surroundings and its proximity to several national parks and monuments.

title: Sympathetic nervous system
text: The sympathetic nervous system (SNS) is a division of the autonomic nervous system that is responsible for preparing the body for physical activity. It is activated in response to stress and triggers the release of hormones such as adrenaline and noradrenaline, which increase heart rate, blood pressure, and breathing rate, and divert blood flow to muscles. The SNS also stimulates the release of glucose into the bloodstream, which provides energy for muscles.

title: Fontana-on-Geneva Lake, Wisconsin
text: Fontana-on-Geneva Lake is a village in Walworth County, Wisconsin, United States. The village is located on the shores of Geneva Lake and is a popular destination for tourists and vacationers. Fontana has a population of 1,493 people and is home to a variety of businesses, including restaurants, shops, and hotels. The village is also home to the Black Point Estate and Gardens, a historic estate that is now open to the public.

title: Square Enix
text: Square Enix is a Japanese video game company that develops and publishes entertainment software worldwide. The company is best known for its role-playing video games, including the Final Fantasy, Dragon Quest, and Kingdom Hearts series, as well as other popular franchises such as Tomb Raider and Deus Ex. Square Enix was formed in 2003 through the merger of Square and Enix, two of Japan's largest video game developers. The company is headquartered in Shinjuku, Tokyo, Japan, and has development studios in Japan, the United States, the United Kingdom, France, and Germany.

title: New towns in the United Kingdom
text: New towns in the United Kingdom were planned and built by the government to address the post-war housing shortage and to relieve population pressures in major cities. Established by the New Towns Act of 1946, they were designed to create self-contained communities with a mix of residential, industrial, and commercial areas, along with amenities such as schools, hospitals, and cultural facilities. These new towns, such as Crawley, Harlow, and Milton Keynes, played a significant role in shaping the urban landscape of the United Kingdom.

title: Douglas County, Colorado
text: Douglas County is a county located in the central part of the U.S. state of Colorado. As of the 2020 census, the population was 375,294, making it the seventh-most populous county in Colorado. The county seat is Castle Rock. Douglas County is one of the fastest-growing counties in Colorado, with a growth rate of 2.5% per year. The county is home to a number of large employers, including DISH Network, Lockheed Martin, and Charles Schwab. Douglas County is also a popular tourist destination, with attractions such as the Red Rocks Amphitheatre and the Colorado Trail.

title: Extreme ultraviolet Imaging Telescope
text: The Extreme ultraviolet Imaging Telescope (EIT) is an instrument on the Solar and Heliospheric Observatory (SOHO) spacecraft. It was designed to study the Sun's corona in extreme ultraviolet light, and has been used to make a wide variety of discoveries about the Sun's atmosphere. EIT was built by a consortium of scientists from the United States, the United Kingdom, and Norway. It was launched into space on December 2, 1995, and has been operating continuously since then. EIT has made many important discoveries about the Sun, including the existence of coronal holes, the structure of the solar wind, and the nature of solar flares.

title: Jeffrey Combs
text: Jeffrey Combs is an American actor best known for his roles in horror and science fiction films and television shows. He has appeared in over 200 films and television shows, including the "Star Trek" franchise, the "Re-Animator" series, and the "Fright Night" franchise. Combs is also a prolific voice actor, having voiced characters in numerous animated films and video games. He is known for his distinctive voice and his ability to play a wide range of characters, from villains to heroes to comedic characters.

title: Levelock, Alaska
text: Levelock, Alaska, is an unincorporated community located on Amaknak Island, part of the Aleutian Islands in the southwestern part of the state. It is situated on the northern shore of Captains Bay, approximately 5 miles (8 km) northeast of the city of Unalaska. Levelock was established in the late 19th century as a fox farming settlement and was once home to a cannery and a post office. Today, the community has a population of around 50 people and relies primarily on commercial fishing and tourism for its economy.

title: Heydar Aliyev
text: Heydar Aliyev was an Azerbaijani politician who served as the third President of Azerbaijan from 1993 to 2003. He played a key role in shaping the country's independence and development after the collapse of the Soviet Union. Aliyev's policies focused on economic reforms, political stability, and strengthening Azerbaijan's international relations. He is credited with bringing stability and economic growth to Azerbaijan, as well as laying the foundation for the country's modern statehood.

title: Abductive reasoning
text: Abductive reasoning, also known as inference to the best explanation, is a form of logical inference that seeks to find the most plausible explanation for a given set of observations. Unlike deductive reasoning, which draws a definite conclusion from a set of premises, abductive reasoning produces a hypothesis that is not necessarily certain but is supported by the available evidence. Abductive reasoning is often used in scientific inquiry, medical diagnosis, and everyday decision-making.

title: Rachel Carson
text: Rachel Carson (1907-1964) was an American marine biologist, conservationist, and author whose influential book "Silent Spring" (1962) raised public awareness about the dangers of pesticides, particularly DDT, and sparked the environmental movement. Carson's work led to the establishment of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and a nationwide ban on DDT. She is considered one of the founders of the modern environmental movement and a pioneer in the field of ecology.

title: American Chemical Society
text: The American Chemical Society (ACS) is the world's largest scientific society and a leading publisher of peer-reviewed scientific journals. Founded in 1876, ACS has 158,000 members who work in various fields of chemistry, including academia, industry, government, and education. The society's mission is to advance the chemical sciences and their applications to benefit society. ACS offers a range of programs and services to its members, including conferences, workshops, and publications. It also advocates for policies that support the chemical sciences.

title: Apostles' Creed
text: The Apostles' Creed is a statement of Christian belief that has been used in Christian liturgy for centuries. It is believed to have originated in the early church, and it is used by many Christian denominations today. The creed is named after the twelve apostles of Jesus, who are said to have been the first to believe in and spread his teachings. The creed consists of twelve articles of faith, which summarize the basic beliefs of Christianity. These articles include the belief in one God, the Father Almighty, maker of heaven and earth; in Jesus Christ, his only Son, our Lord; and in the Holy Spirit.

title: Arkansas Razorbacks
text: The Arkansas Razorbacks are the athletic teams that represent the University of Arkansas. The Razorbacks compete in the Southeastern Conference (SEC) of the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division I. The Razorbacks have won 41 national championships in various sports, including football, basketball, baseball, and track and field. The Razorbacks are known for their passionate fan base, which is known as the Razorback Nation. The Razorbacks' home stadium is Donald W. Reynolds Razorback Stadium in Fayetteville, Arkansas.

title: SS Canberra
text: SS Canberra, a passenger liner operated by P&O Orient Lines, was built in 1960 and entered service in 1961. It was known for its luxurious accommodations and grand public spaces. Canberra sailed on cruises and transatlantic crossings, becoming a popular choice for travelers. In 1974, the ship was purchased by Carnival Cruise Lines and renamed SS Mardi Gras. It continued to serve as a cruise ship until its retirement in 1993. Canberra was then sold for scrap and dismantled in 1997.

title: Grand tourer
text: A grand tourer, shortened to GT, is a high-performance automobile designed for high-speed and long-distance driving, typically with a focus on style, comfort, and luxury. GT cars often combine the performance of a sports car with the practicality and comfort of a sedan. They typically feature powerful engines, sophisticated suspension systems, and luxurious cabins. Notable examples of grand tourers include the Aston Martin DB9, the BMW 8 Series, and the Mercedes-Benz S-Class Coupe.

title: Wink, Texas
text: Wink, Texas, is an unincorporated community in Winkler County, named after Texas Governor Charles A. Culberson, whose nickname was "Charlie Wink." Once a thriving oil town in the early 20th century, Wink's population declined with the oil industry. Despite its small size, Wink is known for its iconic water tower, painted to resemble a giant oil derrick. The town is also home to the Wink Westerners Museum, showcasing the area's oil boom history.

title: Norway, Wisconsin
text: Norway, Wisconsin, is a village in Racine County, Wisconsin, United States. The population was 850 at the 2020 census. Norway is located within the Town of Norway. The village was founded in 1834 by a group of Norwegian immigrants. Norway is home to the Norwegian Lutheran Church, which was founded in 1843 and is the oldest Norwegian Lutheran church in the United States. The village also has a library, a post office, and a hardware store.

title: Biodefense
text: Biodefense is the protection against biological warfare or bioterrorism. It involves measures taken to prevent, detect, and respond to the intentional or accidental release of biological agents, such as bacteria, viruses, or toxins. Biodefense strategies include surveillance, immunization, and the development of diagnostic and therapeutic countermeasures. International cooperation is critical in preventing and mitigating biothreats, and organizations such as the World Health Organization play a key role in coordinating global efforts. Effective biodefense requires a multidisciplinary approach involving public health, law enforcement, military, and intelligence agencies.

title: Mae Questel
text: Mae Questel (September 13, 1908 – January 4, 1998) was an American actress and comedian. She was best known as the voice of Betty Boop, Olive Oyl, and many other cartoon characters for Fleischer Studios and Famous Studios. Questel was born in New York City in 1908 and began her career as a vaudeville performer. In the early 1930s she began working for Fleischer Studios, where she created the voice of Betty Boop. She continued to voice Betty Boop for over 50 years and appeared in over 100 cartoons.

title: Vehicle identification number
text: A vehicle identification number (VIN) is a unique code assigned to a specific motor vehicle. It is used by manufacturers to track vehicles and to ensure that each vehicle is unique. VINs are typically 17 characters long and contain information about the vehicle's make, model, year of manufacture, and other details. VINs are used by law enforcement agencies to identify stolen vehicles and by insurance companies to track vehicle ownership.

title: Chariot
